aw Association blog on Constitutional Reform]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141211140036/http://www.consoc.org.uk/other-content/about-us/discover-the-facts/what-is-the-british-constitution/ The Constitution Society feature on What is the British Constitution?]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150415081918/https://constitutionuk.com/ LSE - A New UK Constitution]\n* [http://constitution-unit.com/about UCL Constitution Unit - About]\n* [http://centreonconstitutionalchange.ac.uk ESRC Centre on Constitutional Change]\n* [http://www.democraticaudit.com Democratic Audit UK]\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/research/notes-on-parliament-and-constitution/ The Parliament and Constitution Centre]\n* [http://conlawfiles.org/chronology/ Constitutional Law Chronology]\n* [https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/United_Kingdom_2013?lang=en Full Constitution of England - Constitute Project]\n* [https://laws.londoninternational.ac.uk/2015/03/16/constitutional-statutes/ Constitutional Statutes]: including discussion of later cases e.g. ''Robinson v Secretary of State for Northern Ireland'' [2002] UKHL 32, ''BH v Lord Advocate'' [2012] UKSC 24, ''R (HS2 Action Alliance Ltd) v Secretary of State for Transport'' [2014] UKSC 3.\n{{Constitution of Europe}}\n{{English law types}}\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constitution of the United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Constitution of the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:Government of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politics of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English constitutionalists]]\n[[Category:Uncodified constitutions]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "Glorious Revolution 1688(a redirect) \u2192Glorious Revolution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Devil May Cry", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game series}}\n{{about||the video game|Devil May Cry (video game)|the novels|Devil May Cry (novels)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title = Devil May Cry\n| image = DMC-logo.png\n| caption = \n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[hack and slash]]\n| developer = {{ubl|[[Capcom]]|[[Ninja Theory]]}}\n| publisher = Capcom\n| creator = [[Hideki Kamiya]]\n| platforms = {{plainlist|\n* [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n* [[iOS]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Mobile game|Mobile]]\n* [[Nintendo Switch]]\n* [[PlayStation 2]]\n* [[PlayStation 3]]\n* [[PlayStation 4]]\n* [[Shield Android TV]]\n* [[Xbox 360]]\n* [[Xbox One]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]''\n| first release date = August 23, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening|Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition]]''<sub>(Switch)</sub>\n| latest release date = February 20, 2020\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''''Devil May Cry'''''|\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb \u30e1\u30a4 \u30af\u30e9\u30a4|Debiru Mei Kurai|lead=yes}} is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[hack and slash]] video game series developed and published by [[Capcom]] and created by [[Hideki Kamiya]]. The series centers on the monster hunter [[Dante (Devil May Cry)|Dante]] and his efforts to avenge his mother's murder. Its gameplay consists of combat scenes in which the player must attempt to extend long chains of attacks, avoiding damage and exhibiting stylized combat; this combat, along with time and the number of items collected and used, are considered in grading the player's performance. Across the series, new characters with unique skills are available.\n\nThe series alludes to [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''. Hideki Kamiya created ''Devil May Cry'' after a failed attempt to develop a ''[[Resident Evil]]''; Kamiya wanted to create a game with more action features, something which Capcom felt the series did not need. The games were directed by [[Hideaki Itsuno]] and writer [[Bingo Morihashi]]. Capcom announced a new game, ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'' (developed by [[Ninja Theory]] and Capcom), during the 2010 [[Tokyo Game Show]]. A high-definition remastering of the three [[PlayStation 2]] titles was released for [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] in 2012, and in 2018 for the [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Personal computer|PC]]. The latest game is ''[[Devil May Cry 5]]'', which was released on March 8, 2019.\n\nThe series has been successful; the main entries have sold several million copies and received Capcom's Platinum Title award. The success of the video-game series has led to  [[comic book]]s, [[novelization]]s, an animated series, guides, collectibles, publications, and a variety of [[action figure]]s. Critical response to the gameplay [[Combo (video games)|combos]] has been positive, although the games' narrative was considered simple until the third installment.\n\n==<span id=\"Overview\"></span>Game overview==\n{{Video game timeline\n| 2001 = ''Devil May Cry''\n| 2003 = ''Devil May Cry 2''\n| 2005 = ''Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening''\n| 2008 = Devil May Cry 4''\n| 2012 = ''Devil May Cry HD Collection''\n| 2013 = ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]''\n| 2019 = ''Devil May Cry 5''\n}}\n* ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]'': Its gameplay focuses on fast-paced, highly-stylized combat; a high style ranking requires long attack and evasion strings, while avoiding damage. Although the game also features puzzle-solving and exploration elements retained from its survival-horror origins, they are downplayed in favor of action. In later games, the system was modified; players had to vary their attacks to maintain their style rank. The style rank is graded during combat with letters: from worst to best, D, C, B, A, and S. They are also represented by words beginning with the first letter of the class: \"Dull\" for D, for example. The third game introduced \"SS\" and \"SSS\" ranks, and player performance on each [[Level (video gaming)|level]] is ranked similarly.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title = Devil May Cry Instruction Booklet|publisher=[[Capcom]]| year = 2001}}</ref> The Devil Trigger enables a player's character to assume a devilish form with additional powers (based on their current weapon), while the character's strength and speed increase and health is slowly restored.<ref name=\"booklet\"/> \n* ''[[Devil May Cry 2]]'' [[Dante (Devil May Cry)|Dante]] is generally the games' lead character, although most of the games offer other playable characters. The ability to perform combination attacks in mid-air and evasion and weapon-change buttons were introduced. With the latter, a player can cycle through ranged weapons without switching to the inventory screen.\n[[File:Devilmaycrygameplay.jpg|thumb|alt=Screenshot|Dante attacks an enemy with the sword Alastor. The word \"Cool!\" assesses the player's performance in combat.]]\n* ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening]]'' added a selection of gameplay styles, allowing the player to focus on favorite techniques or weapons: swords (swordmaster), guns (gunslinger), evasion (trickster) or defense (royal guard). Each of the four styles gains experience points, which unlock more techniques and abilities without costing red orbs (the series' currency). A second weapon-change button was added, allowing the player to cycle through a character's melee weaponry (Devil Arms).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.devilmaycry.org/devil-may-cry-3/styles |title=List of styles in Devil May Cry 3 |publisher=devilmaycry.org |accessdate=April 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917091001/http://www.devilmaycry.org/devil-may-cry-3/styles/ |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The game was re-released as ''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' with new skills for Dante and the ability to play as Vergil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/23/devil-may-cry-3-dantes-awakening-special-edition-review|title=Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening Special Edition Review|author=Dunhan, Jeremy|date=November 22, 2006|publisher=IGN|accessdate=April 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310023352/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/23/devil-may-cry-3-dantes-awakening-special-edition-review|archive-date=March 10, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> \n* ''[[Devil May Cry 4]]'' had a major innovation: Nero's (the main character) Devil Bringer arm, which gives players the ability to pull distant enemies in to be attacked or destroyed. Nero is also armed with a sword which can be throttled up, allowing players to pre-charge it for extra damage on the next hit; with precise timing, it can be charged after each attack for extra damage and style. As Dante, players can switch fighting styles in mid-combat.<ref name=\"dmccapcom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil4/eng/main.html |title=Official English language DMC4 site from Capcom Japan |accessdate=January 31, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124235525/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil4/eng/main.html |archivedate=January 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> An updated version titled ''Special Edition'' was rereleased featuring the ability to play as Vergil as well as Dante's two mates, Trish and Lady.\n*''Devil May Cry HD Collection'': A collection of the series' first three games for the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-cry-compiled-on-ps3-xbox-360/1100-6340448/|title=Devil May Cry compiled on PS3, Xbox 360|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> It was later ported to the PC, PlayStation 4 and Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-cry-hd-collection-coming-to-ps4-xbox-one/1100-6455445/|title=Devil May Cry HD Collection Coming To PS4, Xbox One, And PC|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'' introduced changing environments to the gameplay. Players could reach hidden areas with the Ophion whip and grappling-hook, and the weapon had similar functions to the Devil Bringer in ''Devil May Cry 4''. The environment often \"attacked\" Dante by changing its architecture and infrastructure to a more-hostile form, prompting fast-paced chase sequences and platforming scenarios.<ref>[http://www.siliconera.com/2011/06/14/a-key-addition-to-dmc-devil-may-cry-is-dynamic-changing-environments/ A Key Addition To DmC Devil May Cry Is Dynamic, Changing Environments]. Siliconera (2011-06-14). Retrieved on 2013-08-23.</ref><ref>Bierton, David. (2013-01-27) [http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-dmc-pc-face-off DmC PC - the definitive Devil May Cry experience? \u2022 Face offs \u2022]. Eurogamer.net. Retrieved on 2013-08-23.</ref>\n* ''[[Devil May Cry 5]]'' was released in early 2019. It introduces a character named V, who controls three demons in battle due to his weak physical state. Nero and Dante return as playable characters, although Nero is weaker with the replacement of his Devil Bringer by a mechanical prosthesis.<ref name=\"dailytelegraph\"/>\n*''Devil May Cry: Pinnacle of Combat'': A mobile-phone game by Yunchang Games, based on ''Devil May Cry 3''. Its rendition of Dante's appearance was criticized, and the developers promised to fix it when the game left the beta period for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/devil-may-cry-pinnacle-of-combat-devs-to-address-dantes-face-and-other-feedback-from-beta/|title=Devil May Cry: Pinnacle of Combat Devs To Address Dante's Face And Other Feedback From Beta|website=[[Siliconera]]|date=January 3, 2020|accessdate=January 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103173908/https://www.siliconera.com/devil-may-cry-pinnacle-of-combat-devs-to-address-dantes-face-and-other-feedback-from-beta/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==<span id=\"Series plot\"></span>Plot==\n{{Devil May Cry chronology}}\n{{See also|Characters of Devil May Cry}}\nThe series begins two millennia before the first game with the demon Sparda, the Black Knight, defeating Demon World ruler [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Mundus|Mundus]]. Sparda stops Mundus from conquering the human world by sealing a number of hellgates, sealing Temen-Ni-Gru (the last portal) with a ritual requiring his blood and the aid of a powerful priestess. Sparda meets Eva, who gives birth to his twin sons Dante and Vergil.\n\nThe plot begins with ''Devil May Cry 3'', a year after Dante has a falling-out with Vergil.<ref>''Arkham:'' Is your name Dante? Son of Sparda? ''Dante:'' Where did you hear that? ''Arkham:'' From your brother. He sent this invitation to you. Please accept it. ''Dante:'' Invitation huh? (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> A large tower erupts from the ground near the shop, and Dante interprets it as a challenge from Vergil.<ref>''Dante:'' It's been nearly a year since we last met. Where does the time go? No doubt you've got some fun planned for me. Right Vergil? (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> Dante is defeated in Temen-Ni-Gru by Vergil, who takes his locket and leaves with Arkham. Dante's dormant devil power revives him, and he resumes pursuing his brother. Vergil wants to use the pendants their mother gave them in a ritual to create a portal to the Demon World. The battle is joined by [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Lady|Lady]], who wants to avenge her mother's death by Arkham; Arkham manipulated the three into completing the ritual, which would allow him to acquire Sparda's sword: the Force Edge.<ref>''Jester:'' It was quite a ride, you know! If any of you had died before getting here, our little plan would have gone to waste! Therefore, my job was to get you to battle each other in order to weaken you. But at the same time, I needed to guide you here and make sure you were kept alive. I even went so far as dressing like a complete idiot! (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref><ref>''Arkham:'' He plucks the threads that make us dance, finger and toe! We surrender in joy to the lowest of the foul and rank; we submerge through darkness, rancid filth. Hour by hour, we move downward, ever closer to Hell, in a slow, steady gait. Now, let the world resonate! Sloth! Gluttony! Greed! Envy! Lust! Wrath! And pride! A bell of chaos that tolls human desires! After two thousand long years, the once sealed gate to the demonic world will open! Destruction! Carnage and Despair! Let your instincts drive you! Entrap this world in fear! As its very name Temen-ni-gru strikes terror into the heart of mankind. Then I will become the ultimate ruler of this wasteland engulfed with pandemonium. The demonic power that Sparda once imprisoned&nbsp;... will be mine! (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> Dante and Vergil defeat him, and resume battling each other. The portal begins to close, and Vergil approaches it. Dante pleads with his brother not to go, but Vergil leaps into the Demon World before the portal closes. Vergil is tested and encounters Mundus, his mother's killer. When Lady returns to the human world, she coins the phrase \"devil may cry\"; Dante uses it for the shop.<ref>''Lady:'' Are you crying? ''Dante:'' It's only the rain. ''Lady:'' The rain already stopped. ''Dante:'' Devils never cry. ''Lady:'' I see. Maybe somewhere out there even a devil may cry when he loses a loved one. Don't you think? ''Dante:'' Maybe. (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref><ref>''Lady:'' Oh, speaking of a kind devil, he finally decided on a name for his shop. It took him quite a while to pick one. Want to know the name? Devil May Cry. (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref>\n\nDante is confronted in ''Devil May Cry'' by [[Trish (Devil May Cry)|Trish]], who reveals that Mundus is planning to return and only a descendant of Sparda can defeat him.<ref>''Trish:'' Yes, his powers were sealed by Sparda, he's attempting to take control of the human world again. He has been preparing to open the gate on&nbsp;... Mallet Island. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> He explores Mallet Island (where Mundus is set to return), encountering demons which include Mundus' general:<ref>''Griffon:'' Yours is definitely the power of Sparda&nbsp;... No. Even more so. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> the undead Vergil, Nelo Angelo.<ref>''Dante:'' This stinking hole was the last place that I thought I'd find anyone with some guts. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> As Dante approaches Mundus, he falls into a trap which reveals that Trish is the demon's agent; he saves her, however, because she resembles his mother. Trish saves Dante from Mundus, and Dante realizes his father's power.<ref>''Dante:'' How much longer are you going to keep zapping? Come out and show yourself, Mundus! (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> Dante defeats Mundus when Trish helps him return Mundus to the Demon World.<ref>''Trish:'' Dante, use my power! ''Dante:'' Trish! Okay! (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> Dante and Trish escape as the island collapses, and work together in the Devil Never Cry shop.\n\nIn the ''Devil May Cry: The Animated Series'' anime, Trish is a demon hunter; Dante is the bodyguard of Patty, a young heiress who becomes obsessed with him. Patty's mother is descended from a sorcerer who sealed the power of Abigail, an ancient devil lord. Patty is targeted by Sid, a demon seeking Abigail's power. Lady and Trish fight demons summoned by Sid, and Dante kills him. \n\nDante is invited by [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Lucia|Lucia]] in ''Devil May Cry 2'' to meet her mother, [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Matier|Matier]]. Dante learns that [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Arius|Arius]] is collecting artifacts (Arcana) to summon the demon lord [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Argosax the Chaos|Argosax]].<ref>''Matier:'' Son of Sparda&nbsp;... we must ask this favor, of you&nbsp;... You see, there's a man who's transformed our land into a demon's paradise; his name is Arius. And although he is the president, of an international public corporation&nbsp;... he uses the demon power. Please, deal with Arius and his master for us. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Dante flips a coin, and decides to help.<ref>''(After flipping a coin and noticing the result is heads.)'' ''Dante:'' ... Looks like it's your lucky day. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia confronts Arius, who reveals that he created her.<ref>''Arius:'' You are my creation. ''Lucia:'' Liar! Matier is my mother. ''Arius' secretary removes her mask, revealing the fact her face is identical to Lucia's.'' ''Arius:'' She merely found you when you were about to be disposed of, and then raised you as a soldier. Is that what you consider to be a mother? (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia gives Dante the last of the Arcana before facing Arius alone.<ref>''Lucia:'' But&nbsp;... actually&nbsp;... I do not deserve this power&nbsp;... ''Lucia:'' Bring this to Matier for me&nbsp;... please&nbsp;... I&nbsp;... I've got something that I need to take care of&nbsp;... (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Dante encounters Matier, who asks him to take the Arcana to save Lucia from Arius.<ref>''Matier:'' There is one more thing I need to ask of you, son of Sparda. My daughter went to face Arius all by herself&nbsp;... Please, take these, and save Lucia. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia attacks Arius, but he captures her. Dante arrives, trades the Arcana for Lucia, and attacks Arius (who escapes).<ref>''Arius:'' You cannot win&nbsp;... someone is holding you back... ''Lucia:'' Ugh, forget about me! Kill Arius! ''Dante:'' Don't worry. I've got you... (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> A stream of energy strikes the [[Ouroboros]] tower, and a portal to the demon world opens. Dante and Lucia argue about who will enter, and Dante determines that he will go.<ref>''Lucia:'' But&nbsp;...! ''Dante:'' Let's leave it to fate. Heads, I go; Tails, you go. ''He flips the coin and it lands as heads again'' ''Dante:''See ya around. ''Lucia:'' Don't you want to hear the story about Sparda from&nbsp;... Matier? ''Dante:'' I know&nbsp;... He did the same thing&nbsp;... Hold on to my coin, Lucia. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> After Dante leaves, Arius returns to the human world and Lucia defeats him.<ref>''Arius:'' You are not human! You are just a monster&nbsp;... a monster that I created! ''Lucia:'' Dante told me&nbsp;... Devils never cry! (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> \n\nIn ''Devil May Cry 5'', set several years after ''Devil May Cry 4'', Nero runs a mobile branch of Dante's Devil May Cry business.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sato |title=Devil May Cry 5 Shares A Closer Look At Nero And His Stylish Action |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/06/10/devil-may-cry-5-shares-closer-look-nero-stylish-action/ |website=Siliconera |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=June 10, 2018 }}</ref> He befriends Nico, a weapons artist and descendant of the gunsmith who crafted Dante's Ebony and Ivory handguns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mamiit |first1=Aaron |title=Here's Everything We Know On 'Devil May Cry 5': Release Date, Story, Gameplay, And More |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/230079/20180613/heres-everything-we-know-on-devil-may-cry-5-release-date-story-gameplay-and-more.htm |website=Tech Times |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=June 13, 2018 }}</ref> Nero's Devil Bringer arm from ''Devil May Cry 4'' is stolen; armed with a [[Prosthesis|prosthetic]] Devil Breaker created by Nico, he leaves with Dante and the demon hunter V to face their \"strongest foe yet\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arif |first1=Shabana |title=Devil May Cry 5 Director Talks Story Details, Playable Demo at Gamescom |url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2018/06/25/devil-may-cry-5-director-talks-story-details-playable-demo-at-gamescom |website=IGN |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Yin-Poole |first1=Wesley |title=Devil May Cry 5's third playable character is V |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-20-devil-may-cry-5s-third-playable-character-is-v |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=September 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the series' timeline had placed ''Devil May Cry 4'' before ''Devil May Cry 2'', it was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] with the release of ''Devil May Cry 5''.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1093463399562993664|user=gypsyOtoko|title=We've changed it- now DMC 4 comes after 2! ^^;|author=Matt Walker|date=7 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Devil May Cry 5's Producer Explains the Series' Timeline Changes |url=https://www.ign.com/videos/2019/03/11/devil-may-cry-5s-producer-explains-the-series-timeline-changes |website=IGN |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'', developed by [[Ninja Theory]], is not part of the timeline and takes place in an alternate universe from the main series.<ref>{{cite web |title=DmC Devil May Cry Takes Place In A Parallel World With A Different Dante |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/10/31/dmc-devil-may-cry-takes-place-in-a-parallel-world-with-a-different-dante/|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n{{see also|Resident Evil 4#Development|l1=Development of Resident Evil 4}}\n[[File:Dante03.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|alt=16th-century painting of Dante Alighieri|The series is loosely based on the ''Divine Comedy'' by Dante Alighieri ''(pictured)''.]]\nAfter the completion of ''[[Resident Evil 2]]'' in 1998, preliminary work on a [[PlayStation 2]] installment of the ''Resident Evil'' series began by Team Little Devil under the direction of [[Hideki Kamiya]].<ref name=\"OkamiTree\">{{cite web|last=Mielke |first=Tuhin |publisher=1UP.com |date=August 18, 2006 |title=The Okami Family Tree |url=http://www.1up.com/features/retroactive-hideki-kamiya |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120605051116/http://www.1up.com/features/retroactive-hideki-kamiya |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=March 29, 2007 }}</ref> Early [[research and development]] included a trip to Spain to examine castles as a basis for the game's environments. Its prototype, however, was a radical departure from the ''Resident Evil'' formula and the [[survival horror]] genre. Kamiya rewrote the story and changed its premise, drawing from [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''<ref name=\"dmc3interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/postmortem-dmc3se|title=Postmortem on DMC3:SE|publisher=1UP.com|accessdate=23 June 2013|author=Mielke, James}}</ref><ref name=\"dmcscenario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil/column/vol010.html |title=\u30b7\u30ca\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u8a71 |author=Hideki Kamiya |date=July 2001 |work=Devil May Cry Column |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306002121/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil/column/vol010.html |archivedate=6 March 2010 |df=dmy |author-link=Hideki Kamiya }}</ref> for ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/094/094860p1.html| title= E3 2001: Interview with Shinji Mikami| publisher=IGN| date=May 17, 2001| accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of the original game, its sequel was not created by Kamiya or Team Little Devils.<ref>{{cite video game |title=[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]] |developer=Team Little Devils |publisher=[[Capcom#Branches and subsidiaries|Capcom Entertainment, Inc.]] |date=17 October 2001 |scene=staff credits}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/i_dmc2_ps2 |title=The Devil's in the detail |date=20 February 2003 |author=Kristan Reed |work=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Eurogamer Network Ltd. |accessdate=19 October 2010}}</ref> Although an unidentified director was placed in charge of the project, Capcom was dissatisfied with their work and assigned [[Hideaki Itsuno]] \"with only 4 to 5 months remaining in development\" to steer the project back on course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-devils-own-capcoms-hideaki-itsuno-on-a-decade-plus-with-dante|title=The Devil's Own: Capcom's Hideaki Itsuno on a Decade-Plus with Dante|date=29 June 2015|author=Bob Mackey |work=[[USgamer]] | accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> Despite Itsuno's limited time on the project, he is the only person credited as director in the final version of the game.<ref>{{cite video game |title=Devil May Cry 2 |developer=[[Capcom]] |publisher=[[Capcom#Branches and subsidiaries|Capcom Entertainment, Inc.]] |date=25 January 2003 |scene=staff credits}}</ref> According to [[Video game producer|producer]] Tsuyoshi Tanaka, the design aim was to make ''Devil May Cry 2'' bigger than its predecessor; Tanaka estimated that the game's environments were about nine times larger than the first.<ref>{{cite web| last = Steinberg| first = Scott|title = GameSpot Preview, page 1|date = 2002-09-18 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/devilmaycry2/news.html?sid=2880617|accessdate = 2008-07-20}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Devil May Cry 2''{{'s}} mixed reception, Capcom decided to develop the next game like the more critically-successful ''Devil May Cry''. Gameplay elements, such as environment size and battle engine, were reconsidered.<ref name=\"Gamedailybiz\">{{cite web|url=http://biz.gamedaily.com/industry/toppers/?id=9336 |title=Devil May Cry 3 Poised for Success |date=2005-04-06 |publisher=GameDaily |author=Brightman, James |accessdate=2007-04-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092141/http://biz.gamedaily.com/industry/toppers/?id=9336 |archivedate=September 29, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> In the original game, Vergil was killed by demons early and his soul was controlled by Mundus; [[Bingo Morihashi]] wanted to create an alternate universe in which Vergil was alive. However, Kamiya gave Morihashi the freedom to rework Vergil's backstory and make him a living teenager for ''Devil May Cry 3''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=211}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of ''Devil May Cry 4'' began shortly after its predecessor's success.<ref name=\"writing\">{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=208}}</ref> The development team had 80 members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.videogamesdaily.com/features/dmc4_iv_p3.asp|title=Devil May Cry 4: Kobayashi Interview|date=January 2, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2018|publisher=Video Games Daily}}</ref> A new protagonist was discussed many times at Capcom, but was not approved until producer [[Hiroyuki Kobayashi (producer)|Hiroyuki Kobayashi]] said that Dante had to be in the game.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=213}}</ref> Kobashi said before the game's release that they wanted to make Dante seem significantly more powerful than Nero, to create an obvious difference between the strength of a \"veteran\" compared to a \"rookie\".<ref name=\"very long interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3165697 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130116034927/http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3165697 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 16, 2013 |title=Previews: Devil May Cry 4 |author=James Mielke |website=1UP.com |date=January 31, 2008 |accessdate=February 25, 2008 }}</ref> Writer Morihashi collaborated with film director Yuji Shimomura, who worked on the earlier games. Morihashi left Capcom at one point, but returned at Itsuno's request. It took him a year to finish writing the game; he had difficulty with the characterization of Nero, the new protagonist. Dante returned as a supporting character.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=209}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the fourth game was a commercial and critical success, the staff considered rebooting the series because other game series had better sales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-22-dmc-devil-may-cry-interview |title=DmC: Devil May Cry|publisher=Eurogamer |date=September 22, 2010 |accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref> They chose Ninja Theory, impressed with their work on ''[[Heavenly Sword]]'' (which the staff thought would work with a ''Devil May Cry'' game).<ref name=\"xbuttoninter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2012-10-17|title=The X Button In the Details|publisher=Anime News Network |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=October 17, 2012|author=Ciolek, Todd}}</ref> However, in 2013 Itsuno expressed interest in developing a fifth installment.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dualshockers.com/2013/10/21/dragons-dogma-director-wants-to-make-a-sequel-on-ps4-also-rival-schools-3-and-devil-may-cry-5/ |title = Dragon's Dogma Director Wants to Make a Sequel on PS4, Also Rival Schools 3 and Devil May Cry 5|date = October 21, 2013}}</ref> It was originally thought that Itsuno intended for the series to go on hiatus or end if ''Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition'' was not a commercial success,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/game/content/?p=19420&redirect_stop=1 |title=\u7b2c\u4e09\u5341\u4e09\u56de\u3000\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u304c\u6b69\u3080\u9b54\u754c\u3078\u306e\u9053\uff08\u5f8c\u7de8\uff09 |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=2015-06-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612163031/http://www.capcom.co.jp/game/content/?p=19420&redirect_stop=1 |archivedate=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but he said in a GameSpot interview that the series' future did not depend on ''Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sales. He alleviated fears that ''DmC: Devil May Cry''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sales would kill the series, confirming that Capcom was satisfied with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-crys-future-isnt-tied-to-how-well-devil-/1100-6428432/|title=Devil May Cry's Future isn't Tied to how well Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition sells}}</ref> In mid-January 2016, Itsuno tweeted that he had begun work on a new project.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=tomqe|author=Hideaki Itsuno|number=687098966815543297|date=13 January 2016|title=Happy New Year! The next project has already begun. Please wait to look forward to but can not be announced.}}</ref> Reuben Langdon and Johnny Yong Bosch, who had done voice acting and motion capture for Dante and Nero in ''Devil May Cry 4'', took pictures of themselves in motion-capture gear in March 2016; this led to speculation that a new ''Devil May Cry'' game was in development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gametyrant.com/news/screen-shot-of-mocap-actors-lead-to-devil-may-cry-5-rumor|title=Screen Shot Of Mocap Actors Lead To DEVIL MAY CRY 5 Rumor|website=GameTyrant|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref> According to Capcom Vancouver, \"It's not a game that [they] announced that [they are] working on at [their] studio\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2016/08/01/devil-may-cry-5-capcom-weighs-in/ |title = Capcom Posts Vague Answer when Quizzed About Devil May Cry 5|date = August 2, 2016}}</ref> On May 17, 2018, the domain name \"DevilMayCry5.com\" was registered under Capcom's Onamae domain register.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gematsu.com/2018/06/devil-may-cry-5-domain-name-registered | title=Devil May Cry 5 domain name registered| date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry 5'', featuring the return of Dante and Nero, was confirmed at [[E3 2018]] for release the following year.<ref>[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-devil-may-cry-5-confirmed-at-xbox-one-pres/1100-6459608/ E3 2018: Devil May Cry 5 Confirmed At Xbox One Press Conference], GameSpot</ref>  Most of the team had worked on the recently-released ''Resident Evil 7'', and were experienced with the [[game engine]]; Itsuno was influenced by his work in ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]'' to provide content appealing to new gamers, but also felt that making the game challenging would appeal to long-time fans.<ref name=\"itsuno\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/29/18284532/devil-may-cry-5-hideaki-itsuno-interview-gdc-2019|title=Devil May Cry 5's director wanted to prove pure action games still had a place|date=March 29, 2019|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=June 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629173831/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/29/18284532/devil-may-cry-5-hideaki-itsuno-interview-gdc-2019|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Other members of the staff had worked on the reboot game ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'', but the Osaka team was more willing to make a sequel to the fourth installment of the main series. The team listened to fan opinion about previous games, to ensure that the new game appealed to them; an \"auto\" mode facilitated combos.<ref name=\"osaka\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/27/devil-may-cry-5-interview-capcom-satisfying-fans-balancing-difficulty-learning-ninja-theory/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=June 29, 2019|title=Devil May Cry 5 interview: Capcom on satisfying fans, balancing difficulty and learning from Ninja Theory|date=September 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629173827/https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/27/devil-may-cry-5-interview-capcom-satisfying-fans-balancing-difficulty-learning-ninja-theory/|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Itsuno was moved to tears by a film in which three robots combined into a giant robot to overcome their foe, and wanted to create similar moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/devil-may-cry-5s-director-tells-us-how-they-made-combat-1833642299|title=Devil May Cry 5's Director Tells Us How They Made Combat Feel So Damn Good|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=June 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080028/https://kotaku.com/devil-may-cry-5s-director-tells-us-how-they-made-combat-1833642299|archive-date=9 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He wanted to convey the style of a Hollywood movie such as [[Marvel Studios|Marvel]]'s ''[[Avengers (film series)|Avengers]]'' series.<ref name=\"ruliweb\">{{cite web|url=https://m.ruliweb.com/news/read/117389#csidx3745535f1bbf4c0b1cb92aa605dd106|title=\ub370\ube4c \uba54\uc774 \ud06c\ub77c\uc774 5, \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\ubb3c \uac19\uc740 \uc52c \uc794\ub729 \ub123\uc5c8\ub2e4|publisher=Ruliweb|accessdate=June 30, 2019}}</ref> Kamiya, currently working at [[PlatinumGames]], was interested in making a remake of the first installment and a crossover game with Dante and [[Bayonetta (character)|Bayonetta]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.siliconera.com/2017/11/20/hideki-kamiya-wants-viewtiful-joe-dmc-remake-dante-x-bayonneta-crossover/ | title = Hideki Kamiya Wants To Do A Viewtiful Joe Or DMC Remake, And A Dante x Bayonetta Crossover | date = 20 November 2017 | work = Siliconera }}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n===Light novels===\nThe series has a number of print adaptations. Two [[Devil May Cry (novels)|''Devil May Cry'' light novels]], written by Shinya Goikeda and illustrated by [[Shirow Miwa]], were published in Japan in 2002 and translated and published in the United States in 2006. The first, ''Devil May Cry Volume 1'', was published in Japan in conjunction with the release of the first game and explores Dante in an adventure set before the events of the game. The second, entitled ''Devil May Cry Volume 2'' in the US, was published in Japan to coincide with the release of the second game and is set after the events of the first game. [[Tokyopop]] published the books in the United States in June and November 2006, respectively.<ref name=\"AmazonDMC1\">{{cite book| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry Volume 1| isbn = 1598164503| author1 = Capcom| last2 = Goikeda| first2 = Shinya| date = June 13, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"AmazonDMC2\">{{cite book| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry Volume 2| isbn = 1598164511}}</ref>\n\nBingo Morihashi wrote a ''Devil May Cry 4'' novel entitled ''Devil May Cry 4 Deadly Fortune''. The two-volume novel, published in Japan in 2009, has a number of scenes which were not included in the original game due to time constraints.<ref name=\"novel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/04/_deadly_fortune.html|title=\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u30e1\u30a4\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\uff14 -Deadly Fortune-1|publisher=[[Capcom]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=2 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603031554/http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/04/_deadly_fortune.html|archive-date=3 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/07/_deadly_fortune_1.html |title=\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u30e1\u30a4\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\uff14 -Deadly Fortune-2 |publisher=[[Capcom]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=2 May 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602104915/http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/07/_deadly_fortune_1.html |archivedate= 2 June 2013 |df= }}</ref> A prequel novel by Morihashi, set before ''Devil May Cry 5'' and leading to the beginning of the game, was published on March 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry 5 -Before the Nightmare-|publisher=Kadokawa|year=2019|isbn=978-4041080924}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and manga===\nThree issues of a comic adaptation of the first game were published by the Canadian [[Dreamwave Productions]] in 2004, but the series was left unfinished when the company went bankrupt the following year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=4625 | title=Dreamwave Productions closes up shop |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] | accessdate=April 23, 2007}}</ref> On July 25, 2008, [[WildStorm]] (a [[DC Comics]] [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]]) and [[Capcom]] announced that they would collaborate on a ''Devil May Cry'' [[American comic book|comic-book]] series. Details about the series were planned to be announced at a later date,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5030369/resident-evil-and-devil-may-cry-comics-on-the-way |title=Resident Evil And Devil May Cry Comics On The Way |author=Mike Fahey |publisher=Kotaku |date=July 29, 2008 |accessdate=August 31, 2008}}</ref> but no new information has been provided.\n\nTwo volumes of a planned three-part [[Devil May Cry 3 (manga)|''Devil May Cry 3'' manga]] series have been published in Japan and the United States. Set a year before the events of ''Devil May Cry 3'', the manga describes how the characters come to be where they are at the beginning of the game.\n\nOn March 7, 2019, Capcom announced that a tie-in manga entitled ''Devil May Cry 5 Visions of V'' would be serialized on the Japanese manga-hosting site Line Manga (LINE \u30de\u30f3\u30ac).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil5/news/book190308.html |title=Visions of V Announced|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The manga's prologue was published before the serialization began. Illustrated by Tomio Ogata, the manga (only available in Japan) would update every other Sunday beginning on April 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ExtraVirgin_OO/status/1103624818874703872 |title=Tomio Ogata's Visions of V|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://manga.line.me/product/periodic?id=Z0000410 |title=Visions of V LINE MANGA|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-03-09/devil-may-cry-5-game-gets-manga-spinoff-about-v/.144360|title=Devil May Cry 5 Game Gets Manga Spinoff About V|date=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nAn [[anime]] series, ''[[Devil May Cry: The Animated Series]]'', premiered on Japan's [[Wowow]] TV network on June 12, 2007. The 12-episode series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://activeanime.com/html/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=3851 |title=ActiveAnime:Devil May Cry Anime and Pre Site Opening |accessdate=January 23, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070417100910/http://activeanime.com/html/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=3851 |archivedate=April 17, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dmc-tv.com | title=Devil May Cry anime official site (in Japanese) | accessdate=January 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Devil May Cry: The Animated Series|date=2019-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Devil_May_Cry:_The_Animated_Series&oldid=892409674|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> produced by [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]], was directed by Shin Itagaki. Bingo Morihashi, a writer of the third and fourth games, was one of its writers.\n\nIn November 2018, [[Adi Shankar]] announced that he had acquired the rights to produce a ''Devil May Cry'' animated series. Shankar, who has been completing a similar [[Castlevania (TV series)|animated series]] for Konami's ''[[Castlevania]]'' franchise, said that he considered both series part of a shared \"bootleg multiverse\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/16/devil-may-cry-series-joins-castlevania-in-new-multiverse-from-adi-shankar | title = Devil May Cry Series Joins Castlevania In New Multiverse From Adi Shankar | first = David | last = Griffin | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nOn February 28, 2011, it was announced that [[Screen Gems]] (which made ''Resident Evil'' into a [[Resident Evil (film series)|film series]]) had purchased feature-film rights to the ''Devil May Cry'' series.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118033032?refCatId=13 | work=Variety | first1=Andrew | last1=Stewart | first2=Marc | last2=Graser | title='Devil May Cry' videogame heading to bigscreen | date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> Kyle Ward would write the screenplay for the film (based on ''DmC: Devil May Cry''), which would be Dante's origin story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/e3-2011-devil-may-cry-film-based-on-new-game-6318318|title=E3 2011: Devil May Cry Film Based On New Game|author=Tom Magrino|publisher=Gamespot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crossmap.com/news/devil-may-cry-movie-release-date-updates-storyline-what-this-game-turned-movie-is-going-to-turn-out-to-be-15585|title=Devil May Cry Movie Release Date, Updates, Storyline: What this Game Turned Movie is Going to Turn Out to Be|publisher=Cross Map|last=Lavigne|first=Patty|date=January 15, 2015|access-date=December 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208174111/http://www.crossmap.com/news/devil-may-cry-movie-release-date-updates-storyline-what-this-game-turned-movie-is-going-to-turn-out-to-be-15585|archive-date=December 8, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthhealthmag.com/articles/32990/20160118/devil-may-cry-movie-movie-adaptation.htm|title='Devil May Cry' Movie Adaptation Still Happening? Norman Reedus Or Brad Pitt To Play Dante?|publisher=Youth Health Mag|last=Rajasekhar|first=Gouravaram|date=January 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Plays===\nCapcom produced ''Sengoku Basara vs. Devil May Cry'' a staged amalgam of the ''Devil May Cry'' and ''[[Sengoku Basara]]'' series, in August 2015. In the play, Dante, Lady, Trish, and Vergil encounter mysterious historical ruins while chasing a devil and are sent back in time to Japan's [[Warring States period]]; there, they meet Date Masamune, Sanada Yukimura and other characters from the ''Sengoku Basara'' franchise. The play ran at the AiiA 2.5 Theater in Tokyo for 18 performances. [[Masanari Ujigawa]] wrote and directed the play, and [[Hideaki Itsuno]] and [[Izaki Matsuno]] collaborated on the scenery. [[Kazushi Miyakoda]] and [[Tetsuya Yamaura]] were the producers, supervised by [[Hiroyuki Kobayashi (producer)|Hiroyuki Kobayashi]] and [[Makoto Yamamoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-08/more-cast-revealed-for-sengoku-basara-vs-devil-may-cry-stage-play/.87955|title=More Cast Revealed for Sengoku Basara vs. Devil May Cry Stage Play|date=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry: The Live Hacker'', a musical, ran for 13 performances in March 2019 at [[Zepp|Zepp DiverCity]] in Tokyo. Jun Yoriko wrote and directed the musical and its video,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-01-18/devil-may-cry-the-live-hacker-reveals-cast-members-in-costume/.142266|title=Devil May Cry: The Live Hacker Reveals Cast Members in Costume|date=January 18, 2019}}</ref> and a DVD was released in late August of that year.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dmc-livehacker.com/ | title=Devil May Cry \u30fcthe Live Hacker\u30fc}}</ref>\n\n==In other games==\n''Devil May Cry'' characters appear in the [[PlayStation]] versions of the ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'' games, another Capcom series created by Hideki Kamiya; Dante is a playable character in the [[PlayStation 2]] port of the first ''Viewtiful Joe''. The [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]] version of ''[[Viewtiful Joe: Red Hot Rumble]]'' also includes Dante and costumes based on Vergil, Trish, Sparda, Marionette, and Plasma.\n\nIn a deal between Capcom and [[Atlus]], ''[[Megami Tensei]]'' character designer [[Kazuma Kaneko]] created Dante and Vergil's demonic forms in ''Devil May Cry 3''. In return, Atlus included Dante in his ''Devil May Cry 2'' costume as a character in an enhanced release of ''[[Shin Megami Tensei: Nocturne]]'' (''Maniax'' in Japan). The English localization of ''Nocturne'' was based on the game's ''Maniax'' edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlus.com/smt/faqs.html|title=Atlus USA presents Shin Megami Tensei: Nocturne|publisher=[[Atlus]]|accessdate=April 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDante and Trish are playable characters in ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 3: Fate of Two Worlds]]'', and Vergil, Dante and Trish are playable characters in its ''[[Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3]]'' update. Dante and Vergil retain their Kazuma Kaneko-designed Devil Trigger forms, since they are based on the third game of the ''Devil May Cry'' series.\n\nThe ''DmC: Devil May Cry'' version of Dante is a playable character in ''[[PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale]]'', and he is a playable character in ''[[Project X Zone]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS as half of a pair with ''[[Darkstalkers]]''{{'}} [[Demitri Maximoff]]; Lady is a separate character. Dante returns in its sequel, ''[[Project X Zone 2]]'', with Vergil; Vergil's future self, Nelo Angelo, is a rival character.\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG Series Reviews\n| updated = March 11, 2019\n| game1 = [[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]\n| mc1 = (PS2) 94 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry |title=''Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game2 = [[Devil May Cry 2]] \n| mc2 = (PS2) 68 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-2 |title=''Devil May Cry 2'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game3 = [[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening]]\n| mc3 = (PS2) 87 <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3-special-edition |title=''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 66 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-3-special-edition |title=''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game4 = [[Devil May Cry 4]]\n| mc4 = (PS3) 84 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/devil-may-cry-4 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(X360) 84 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/devil-may-cry-4 |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 78<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-4 |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game5 = [[DmC: Devil May Cry]]\n| mc5 = (X360) 86 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PS3) 85 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 85 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game6 = [[Devil May Cry 5]]\n| mc6 = (PC) 90 <ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for PC Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><br>(PS4) 88 <ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for PlayStation 4 Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><br>(XONE) 87 <ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for Xbox One Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nBy December 31, 2019, the ''Devil May Cry'' series had sold 21 million units worldwide;<ref>[http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/salesdata.html CAPCOM | Game Series Sales]</ref> each installment was a Capcom Platinum Title, selling over a million units.<ref name=\"capcomplatinum\">{{cite web|url=http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/data/million.html |title=Platinum Titles |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=April 4, 2007 |date=January 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211163520/http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/data/million.html |archivedate=February 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> As of December 2019, ''Devil May Cry 5'' had sold 3.1&nbsp;million copies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Platinum Titles |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/million.html |website=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201214236/http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/million.html |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe series has received generally-positive reviews. In 2010, [[IGN]] ranked ''Devil May Cry'' number 42 and ''Devil May Cry 3'' number 18 on its \"Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/42 |title=Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |publisher=IGN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201231437/http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/42 |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/18 |title=Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |publisher=IGN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103190544/http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/18 |archivedate=January 3, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' gameplay has been praised as innovative.<ref name=\"Eurogamer\">{{cite web|author=John Bye |date=2001-08-12 |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2281 |title=Devil May Cry Review |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=2008-07-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930035826/http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2281 |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gamecritics\"/><ref name=\"ElectricPlayground\">{{cite web|author=James Tapia| url=http://www.elecplay.com/reviews_article.php?article=7180| title=Devil May Cry Review| publisher=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]| accessdate=2008-07-20| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610080414/http://www.elecplay.com/reviews_article.php?article=7180 <!--Added by H3llBot-->| archivedate=2008-06-10}}</ref> ''Devil May Cry'' has been cited as beginning a subgenre of \"extreme combat\" action games, which focus on powerful heroes fighting hordes of foes with stylized action.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bateman | first = Chris | author2 = Richard Boon | title = 21st Century Game Design | publisher = Charles River Media | pages = [https://archive.org/details/21stcenturygamed0000bate/page/246 246\u2013247] | date = August 29, 2005 | isbn = 978-1-58450-429-0 | title-link = 21st Century Game Design }}</ref> It has been described as the first game that \"successfully captured the twitch-based, relentlessly free-flowing gameplay style of so many classic [[2D computer graphics|2D]] action games\".<ref name=\"Review1\">{{cite web|last= Ahmed|first= Shahed |date= October 17, 2001|title = Gamespot Devil May Cry review| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/devilmaycry/review.html|accessdate = March 29, 2007 | publisher=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> The series is the standard against which other [[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[hack and slash]] action games are measured, with comparisons in reviews of games such as ''[[God of War (2005 video game)|God of War]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= God of War|publisher=IGN|url= http://ps2.ign.com/objects/661/661321.html#previews| accessdate= April 3, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| date= June 16, 2005| publisher=Playstation World| title= God of War Review |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=120641&site=psw&skip=yes| accessdate= April 3, 2003}}</ref> ''[[Chaos Legion]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last= Varanini|first= Giancarlo| publisher=[[GameSpot]]| date= August 4, 2003| title= Chaos Legion review| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/chaoslegion/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;review| accessdate= April 3, 2007}}</ref> and ''[[Blood Will Tell]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bedigian |first=Louis |publisher=Gamezone |date=September 29, 2004 |title=Blood Will Tell review |url=http://ps2.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r22035.htm |accessdate= April 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070412062309/http://ps2.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r22035.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Devil May Cry 5'' has three protagonists with distinctive abilities, increasing the number of moves available.<ref name=\"vgamer\">{{cite web |title=Devil May Cry 5 review |url=https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review |website=VideoGamer.com |date=6 March 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307112327/https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review |archive-date=7 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"IGN Review\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2019/03/06/devil-may-cry-5-review|title=Devil May Cry 5 Review|last=Saltzman|first=Mitchell|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dailytelegraph\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Olivia |title=Devil May Cry 5 review: Dante and friends return in a stylish and supremely fun demon-hunting blockbuster |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/devil-may-cry-5-review-dante-friends-return-stylish-supremely/ |accessdate=6 March 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306163646/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/devil-may-cry-5-review-dante-friends-return-stylish-supremely/ |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Hiroyuki Kobayashi, the team's work on ''Devil May Cry 4'' influenced Capcom's ''[[Dragon's Dogma]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/dragons-dogma-interview-part-1-from-devils-to-dragons/|title=Dragon's Dogma Interview Part 1: From Devils To Dragons|website=Siliconera|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponse to the series' narrative has been mixed, despite Dante's increased popularity.<ref name=\"Gamecrush\">{{cite web |author=Rocco Inzauto, Edward |url=http://gamecrush.blogspot.com/2007/02/top-10-most-badass-video-game-charaters.html |title=Top 10: Most Badass Video Game Characters |date=February 25, 2007 |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129042015/http://gamecrush.blogspot.com/2007/02/top-10-most-badass-video-game-charaters.html |archivedate=January 29, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Screwattack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelastboss.com/post.phtml?pk=2160 |title=Top ten coolest games |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809013318/http://www.thelastboss.com/post.phtml?pk=2160 |archivedate=August 9, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' popularity led to a line of ''Devil May Cry'' action figures produced by Toycom,<ref name=\"Actionfigures\">{{cite web|author=Borst, Brian |url=http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=2243 |title=Devil May Cry Action Figures review |date=June 1, 2003 |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516220713/http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=2243 |archivedate=May 16, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}<br />{{cite web|author=Borst, Brian |url=http://www.popcultureshock.com/pcs-reviews.php?id=2243 |title=Devil May Cry Action Figures |work=Pop Culture Shock |date=June 4, 2003 |accessdate=January 16, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116193119/http://www.popcultureshock.com/pcs-reviews.php?id=2243 |archivedate=January 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> and [[Kaiyodo]] produced a ''Devil May Cry 2'' and ''Devil May Cry 3'' Dante action figure.<ref name=\"AmazonDMC2 figs\">{{cite web|title=Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry 2 Action Figures |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000HX7YTK |accessdate=April 23, 2007 |df=mdy }}{{dead link|date=February 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"AmazonDMC3\">{{cite web| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry 3 Dante Revoltech action figure| url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000GBN2Y4| accessdate = April 23, 2007}}</ref> \n\nAccording to a gamecritics.com reviewer, the story was overly short and the characters underdeveloped.<ref name=\"Gamecritics\">{{cite web|author=Mike Doolittle |date=2001-11-28 |title=Devil May Cry review |url=http://www.gamecritics.com/review/devilmaycry/main.php |accessdate=2008-07-20 |publisher=Gamecritics.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922214620/http://www.gamecritics.com/review/devilmaycry/main.php |archivedate=2008-09-22 }}</ref> Dante's cockiness was noted as largely absent from ''Devil May Cry 2''.<ref name=\"Gamespy\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.gamespy.com/reviews/february03/dmc2ps2/ |title=Devil May Cry 2 review |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=15 April 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724215125/http://archive.gamespy.com/reviews/february03/dmc2ps2/ |archivedate=24 July 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Railey, Dave\">{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/game/playstation-3-xbox-360/devil-may-cry/hd-collection |title=Devil May Cry: HD Collection |work=[[Anime News Network]] |author=Railey, Dave |date=16 April 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615232002/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/game/playstation-3-xbox-360/devil-may-cry/hd-collection |archivedate=15 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry 3'' and its relationships among the cast in the narrative were found to be superior to Kamiya's original version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/devil-may-cry-3-10/2/|title=Devil May Cry 3|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|publisher=[[Future plc|Future]]|date=July 28, 2004|accessdate=July 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725003106/https://www.gamesradar.com/devil-may-cry-3-10/2/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/04/devil-may-cry-a-series-retrospective-part-iii/|title=Devil May Cry: a series retrospective - part III|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Verizon Communications]]|author=Doee, Mark|date=February 4, 2008|accessdate=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725214710/https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/04/devil-may-cry-a-series-retrospective-part-iii/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3/592530p2.html|title=Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening|work=[[GameSpy]]|publisher=IGN|author=Lopez, Miguel|date=March 1, 2005|accessdate=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026061519/http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3/592530p2.html|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dante's dynamic with Nero in the following game was praised, with critics saying that neither overshadowed the other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-4-review/1900-6185608/|title=Devil May Cry 4 Review|website=GameSpot|accessdate=June 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627005357/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-4-review/1900-6185608/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GIDMC4review\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Game Informer]]| author= Joe, Juba | url=http://gameinformer.com/Games/Review/200803/R08.0205.1105.44993.htm | title= Game Informer: Devil May Cry 4 Review| accessdate=5 February 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080512084303/http://gameinformer.com/Games/Review/200803/R08.0205.1105.44993.htm |archivedate = 12 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"IGNDMC4review\">{{cite web| website= IGN| author= Haynes, Jeff| url= http://ps3.ign.com/articles/849/849224p1.html| title= IGN: Devil May Cry 4 Review (PS3)| accessdate=5 February 2008| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120101200755/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/849/849224p1.html| archive-date= 1 January 2012| url-status= live}}</ref> According to GameCored, many fans were eager to play as Vergil again in ''Devil May Cry 5'' and were disappointed that he was not a playable character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecored.com/devil-may-cry-5-jugar-como-vergil/|title=Devil May Cry 5: \u00bfPodr\u00e1s jugar como Vergil?|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=GameCord|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> ''HobbyConsolas'' hacked into the game to find code which mentioned the character's name, but was unable to determine if Vergil would be playable as downloadable content.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/noticias/devil-may-cry-5-descubren-codigo-cuarto-personaje-jugable-video-386436|title=Devil May Cry 5 - Descubren en el c\u00f3digo a un cuarto personaje jugable (v\u00eddeo)|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=HobbyConsolas|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> ''Devil May Cry 5''{{'}}s handling of its characters and their connections was well-received.<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review-comeback-album/1900-6417099 |title=Devil May Cry 5 Review|last=Espineli|first=Matt|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vgamer\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Devil May Cry series}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.devilmaycry.com/ Capcom USA's ''Devil May Cry'' portal]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060404060314/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil2/ ''Devil May Cry 2'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050225003945/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil3/ ''Devil May Cry 3'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20060125013714/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil3_se/ ''Devil May Cry 3 Special Edition'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil4/ ''Devil May Cry 4'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.capcom.co.jp/devilmaycry/ ''Devil May Cry HD Collection'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.capcom.co.jp/dmc/ ''DmC: Devil May Cry'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil5/ ''Devil May Cry 5'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/game-group/devil-may-cry-series ''Devil May Cry'' series] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Devil May Cry series}}\n{{Franchises by Capcom}}\n{{Divine Comedy navbox}}\n[[Category:Action-adventure video games by series]]\n[[Category:Capcom beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Capcom franchises]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Video games about demons]]\n[[Category:Devil May Cry]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Hack and slash video games by series]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2001]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game series}}\n{{about||the video game|Devil May Cry (video game)|the novels|Devil May Cry (novels)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title = Devil May Cry\n| image = DMC-logo.png\n| caption = \n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[hack and slash]]\n| developer = {{ubl|[[Capcom]]|[[Ninja Theory]]}}\n| publisher = Capcom\n| creator = [[Hideki Kamiya]]\n| platforms = {{plainlist|\n* [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n* [[iOS]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Mobile game|Mobile]]\n* [[Nintendo Switch]]\n* [[PlayStation 2]]\n* [[PlayStation 3]]\n* [[PlayStation 4]]\n* [[Shield Android TV]]\n* [[Xbox 360]]\n* [[Xbox One]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]''\n| first release date = August 23, 2001\n| latest release version = ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening|Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition]]''<sub>(Switch)</sub>\n| latest release date = February 20, 2020\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''''Devil May Cry'''''|\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb \u30e1\u30a4 \u30af\u30e9\u30a4|Debiru Mei Kurai|lead=yes}} is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[hack and slash]] video game series developed and published by [[Capcom]] and created by [[Hideki Kamiya]]. The series centers on the monster hunter [[Dante (Devil May Cry)|Dante]] and his efforts to avenge his mother's murder. Its gameplay consists of combat scenes in which the player must attempt to extend long chains of attacks, avoiding damage and exhibiting stylized combat; this combat, along with time and the number of items collected and used, are considered in grading the player's performance. Across the series, new characters with unique skills are available.\n\nThe series alludes to [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''. Hideki Kamiya created ''Devil May Cry'' after a failed attempt to develop a ''[[Resident Evil]]''; Kamiya wanted to create a game with more action features, something which Capcom felt the series did not need. The games were directed by [[Hideaki Itsuno]] and writer [[Bingo Morihashi]]. Capcom announced a new game, ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'' (developed by [[Ninja Theory]] and Capcom), during the 2010 [[Tokyo Game Show]]. A high-definition remastering of the three [[PlayStation 2]] titles was released for [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] in 2012, and in 2018 for the [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Personal computer|PC]]. The latest game is ''[[Devil May Cry 5]]'', which was released on March 8, 2019.\n\nThe series has been successful; the main entries have sold several million copies and received Capcom's Platinum Title award. The success of the video-game series has led to  [[comic book]]s, [[novelization]]s, an animated series, guides, collectibles, publications, and a variety of [[action figure]]s. Critical response to the gameplay [[Combo (video games)|combos]] has been positive, although the games' narrative was considered simple until the third installment.\n\n==<span id=\"Overview\"></span>Game overview==\n{{Video game timeline\n| 2001 = ''Devil May Cry''\n| 2003 = ''Devil May Cry 2''\n| 2005 = ''Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening''\n| 2008 = Devil May Cry 4''\n| 2012 = ''Devil May Cry HD Collection''\n| 2013 = ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]''\n| 2019 = ''Devil May Cry 5''\n}}\n* ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]'': Its gameplay focuses on fast-paced, highly-stylized combat; a high style ranking requires long attack and evasion strings, while avoiding damage. Although the game also features puzzle-solving and exploration elements retained from its survival-horror origins, they are downplayed in favor of action. In later games, the system was modified; players had to vary their attacks to maintain their style rank. The style rank is graded during combat with letters: from worst to best, D, C, B, A, and S. They are also represented by words beginning with the first letter of the class: \"Dull\" for D, for example. The third game introduced \"SS\" and \"SSS\" ranks, and player performance on each [[Level (video gaming)|level]] is ranked similarly.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title = Devil May Cry Instruction Booklet|publisher=[[Capcom]]| year = 2001}}</ref> The Devil Trigger enables a player's character to assume a devilish form with additional powers (based on their current weapon), while the character's strength and speed increase and health is slowly restored.<ref name=\"booklet\"/> \n* ''[[Devil May Cry 2]]'' [[Dante (Devil May Cry)|Dante]] is generally the games' lead character, although most of the games offer other playable characters. The ability to perform combination attacks in mid-air and evasion and weapon-change buttons were introduced. With the latter, a player can cycle through ranged weapons without switching to the inventory screen.\n[[File:Devilmaycrygameplay.jpg|thumb|alt=Screenshot|Dante attacks an enemy with the sword Alastor. The word \"Cool!\" assesses the player's performance in combat.]]\n* ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening]]'' added a selection of gameplay styles, allowing the player to focus on favorite techniques or weapons: swords (swordmaster), guns (gunslinger), evasion (trickster) or defense (royal guard). Each of the four styles gains experience points, which unlock more techniques and abilities without costing red orbs (the series' currency). A second weapon-change button was added, allowing the player to cycle through a character's melee weaponry (Devil Arms).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.devilmaycry.org/devil-may-cry-3/styles |title=List of styles in Devil May Cry 3 |publisher=devilmaycry.org |accessdate=April 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917091001/http://www.devilmaycry.org/devil-may-cry-3/styles/ |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The game was re-released as ''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' with new skills for Dante and the ability to play as Vergil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/23/devil-may-cry-3-dantes-awakening-special-edition-review|title=Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening Special Edition Review|author=Dunhan, Jeremy|date=November 22, 2006|publisher=IGN|accessdate=April 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310023352/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/23/devil-may-cry-3-dantes-awakening-special-edition-review|archive-date=March 10, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> \n* ''[[Devil May Cry 4]]'' had a major innovation: Nero's (the main character) Devil Bringer arm, which gives players the ability to pull distant enemies in to be attacked or destroyed. Nero is also armed with a sword which can be throttled up, allowing players to pre-charge it for extra damage on the next hit; with precise timing, it can be charged after each attack for extra damage and style. As Dante, players can switch fighting styles in mid-combat.<ref name=\"dmccapcom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil4/eng/main.html |title=Official English language DMC4 site from Capcom Japan |accessdate=January 31, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124235525/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil4/eng/main.html |archivedate=January 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> An updated version titled ''Special Edition'' was rereleased featuring the ability to play as Vergil as well as Dante's two mates, Trish and Lady.\n*''Devil May Cry HD Collection'': A collection of the series' first three games for the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-cry-compiled-on-ps3-xbox-360/1100-6340448/|title=Devil May Cry compiled on PS3, Xbox 360|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> It was later ported to the PC, PlayStation 4 and Xbox Oneo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-cry-hd-collection-coming-to-ps4-xbox-one/1100-6455445/|title=Devil May Cry HD Collection Coming To PS4, Xbox One, And PC|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'' introduced changing environments to the gameplay. Players could reach hidden areas with the Ophion whip and grappling-hook, and the weapon had similar functions to the Devil Bringer in ''Devil May Cry 4''. The environment often \"attacked\" Dante by changing its architecture and infrastructure to a more-hostile form, prompting fast-paced chase sequences and platforming scenarios.<ref>[http://www.siliconera.com/2011/06/14/a-key-addition-to-dmc-devil-may-cry-is-dynamic-changing-environments/ A Key Addition To DmC Devil May Cry Is Dynamic, Changing Environments]. Siliconera (2011-06-14). Retrieved on 2013-08-23.</ref><ref>Bierton, David. (2013-01-27) [http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-dmc-pc-face-off DmC PC - the definitive Devil May Cry experience? \u2022 Face offs \u2022]. Eurogamer.net. Retrieved on 2013-08-23.</ref>\n* ''[[Devil May Cry 5]]'' was released in early 2019. It introduces a character named V, who controls three demons in battle due to his weak physical state. Nero and Dante return as playable characters, although Nero is weaker with the replacement of his Devil Bringer by a mechanical prosthesis.<ref name=\"dailytelegraph\"/>\n*''Devil May Cry: Pinnacle of Combat'': A mobile-phone game by Yunchang Games, based on ''Devil May Cry 3''. Its rendition of Dante's appearance was criticized, and the developers promised to fix it when the game left the beta period for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/devil-may-cry-pinnacle-of-combat-devs-to-address-dantes-face-and-other-feedback-from-beta/|title=Devil May Cry: Pinnacle of Combat Devs To Address Dante's Face And Other Feedback From Beta|website=[[Siliconera]]|date=January 3, 2020|accessdate=January 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103173908/https://www.siliconera.com/devil-may-cry-pinnacle-of-combat-devs-to-address-dantes-face-and-other-feedback-from-beta/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==<span id=\"Series plot\"></span>Plot==\n{{Devil May Cry chronology}}\n{{See also|Characters of Devil May Cry}}\nThe series begins two millennia before the first game with the demon Sparda, the Black Knight, defeating Demon World ruler [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Mundus|Mundus]]. Sparda stops Mundus from conquering the human world by sealing a number of hellgates, sealing Temen-Ni-Gru (the last portal) with a ritual requiring his blood and the aid of a powerful priestess. Sparda meets Eva, who gives birth to his twin sons Dante and Vergil.\n\nThe plot begins with ''Devil May Cry 3'', a year after Dante has a falling-out with Vergil.<ref>''Arkham:'' Is your name Dante? Son of Sparda? ''Dante:'' Where did you hear that? ''Arkham:'' From your brother. He sent this invitation to you. Please accept it. ''Dante:'' Invitation huh? (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> A large tower erupts from the ground near the shop, and Dante interprets it as a challenge from Vergil.<ref>''Dante:'' It's been nearly a year since we last met. Where does the time go? No doubt you've got some fun planned for me. Right Vergil? (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> Dante is defeated in Temen-Ni-Gru by Vergil, who takes his locket and leaves with Arkham. Dante's dormant devil power revives him, and he resumes pursuing his brother. Vergil wants to use the pendants their mother gave them in a ritual to create a portal to the Demon World. The battle is joined by [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Lady|Lady]], who wants to avenge her mother's death by Arkham; Arkham manipulated the three into completing the ritual, which would allow him to acquire Sparda's sword: the Force Edge.<ref>''Jester:'' It was quite a ride, you know! If any of you had died before getting here, our little plan would have gone to waste! Therefore, my job was to get you to battle each other in order to weaken you. But at the same time, I needed to guide you here and make sure you were kept alive. I even went so far as dressing like a complete idiot! (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref><ref>''Arkham:'' He plucks the threads that make us dance, finger and toe! We surrender in joy to the lowest of the foul and rank; we submerge through darkness, rancid filth. Hour by hour, we move downward, ever closer to Hell, in a slow, steady gait. Now, let the world resonate! Sloth! Gluttony! Greed! Envy! Lust! Wrath! And pride! A bell of chaos that tolls human desires! After two thousand long years, the once sealed gate to the demonic world will open! Destruction! Carnage and Despair! Let your instincts drive you! Entrap this world in fear! As its very name Temen-ni-gru strikes terror into the heart of mankind. Then I will become the ultimate ruler of this wasteland engulfed with pandemonium. The demonic power that Sparda once imprisoned&nbsp;... will be mine! (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref> Dante and Vergil defeat him, and resume battling each other. The portal begins to close, and Vergil approaches it. Dante pleads with his brother not to go, but Vergil leaps into the Demon World before the portal closes. Vergil is tested and encounters Mundus, his mother's killer. When Lady returns to the human world, she coins the phrase \"devil may cry\"; Dante uses it for the shop.<ref>''Lady:'' Are you crying? ''Dante:'' It's only the rain. ''Lady:'' The rain already stopped. ''Dante:'' Devils never cry. ''Lady:'' I see. Maybe somewhere out there even a devil may cry when he loses a loved one. Don't you think? ''Dante:'' Maybe. (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref><ref>''Lady:'' Oh, speaking of a kind devil, he finally decided on a name for his shop. It took him quite a while to pick one. Want to know the name? Devil May Cry. (''Devil May Cry 3'') Capcom, 2005</ref>\n\nDante is confronted in ''Devil May Cry'' by [[Trish (Devil May Cry)|Trish]], who reveals that Mundus is planning to return and only a descendant of Sparda can defeat him.<ref>''Trish:'' Yes, his powers were sealed by Sparda, he's attempting to take control of the human world again. He has been preparing to open the gate on&nbsp;... Mallet Island. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> He explores Mallet Island (where Mundus is set to return), encountering demons which include Mundus' general:<ref>''Griffon:'' Yours is definitely the power of Sparda&nbsp;... No. Even more so. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> the undead Vergil, Nelo Angelo.<ref>''Dante:'' This stinking hole was the last place that I thought I'd find anyone with some guts. (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> As Dante approaches Mundus, he falls into a trap which reveals that Trish is the demon's agent; he saves her, however, because she resembles his mother. Trish saves Dante from Mundus, and Dante realizes his father's power.<ref>''Dante:'' How much longer are you going to keep zapping? Come out and show yourself, Mundus! (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> Dante defeats Mundus when Trish helps him return Mundus to the Demon World.<ref>''Trish:'' Dante, use my power! ''Dante:'' Trish! Okay! (''Devil May Cry'') Capcom, 2001</ref> Dante and Trish escape as the island collapses, and work together in the Devil Never Cry shop.\n\nIn the ''Devil May Cry: The Animated Series'' anime, Trish is a demon hunter; Dante is the bodyguard of Patty, a young heiress who becomes obsessed with him. Patty's mother is descended from a sorcerer who sealed the power of Abigail, an ancient devil lord. Patty is targeted by Sid, a demon seeking Abigail's power. Lady and Trish fight demons summoned by Sid, and Dante kills him. \n\nDante is invited by [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Lucia|Lucia]] in ''Devil May Cry 2'' to meet her mother, [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Matier|Matier]]. Dante learns that [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Arius|Arius]] is collecting artifacts (Arcana) to summon the demon lord [[Characters of Devil May Cry#Argosax the Chaos|Argosax]].<ref>''Matier:'' Son of Sparda&nbsp;... we must ask this favor, of you&nbsp;... You see, there's a man who's transformed our land into a demon's paradise; his name is Arius. And although he is the president, of an international public corporation&nbsp;... he uses the demon power. Please, deal with Arius and his master for us. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Dante flips a coin, and decides to help.<ref>''(After flipping a coin and noticing the result is heads.)'' ''Dante:'' ... Looks like it's your lucky day. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia confronts Arius, who reveals that he created her.<ref>''Arius:'' You are my creation. ''Lucia:'' Liar! Matier is my mother. ''Arius' secretary removes her mask, revealing the fact her face is identical to Lucia's.'' ''Arius:'' She merely found you when you were about to be disposed of, and then raised you as a soldier. Is that what you consider to be a mother? (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia gives Dante the last of the Arcana before facing Arius alone.<ref>''Lucia:'' But&nbsp;... actually&nbsp;... I do not deserve this power&nbsp;... ''Lucia:'' Bring this to Matier for me&nbsp;... please&nbsp;... I&nbsp;... I've got something that I need to take care of&nbsp;... (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Dante encounters Matier, who asks him to take the Arcana to save Lucia from Arius.<ref>''Matier:'' There is one more thing I need to ask of you, son of Sparda. My daughter went to face Arius all by herself&nbsp;... Please, take these, and save Lucia. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> Lucia attacks Arius, but he captures her. Dante arrives, trades the Arcana for Lucia, and attacks Arius (who escapes).<ref>''Arius:'' You cannot win&nbsp;... someone is holding you back... ''Lucia:'' Ugh, forget about me! Kill Arius! ''Dante:'' Don't worry. I've got you... (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> A stream of energy strikes the [[Ouroboros]] tower, and a portal to the demon world opens. Dante and Lucia argue about who will enter, and Dante determines that he will go.<ref>''Lucia:'' But&nbsp;...! ''Dante:'' Let's leave it to fate. Heads, I go; Tails, you go. ''He flips the coin and it lands as heads again'' ''Dante:''See ya around. ''Lucia:'' Don't you want to hear the story about Sparda from&nbsp;... Matier? ''Dante:'' I know&nbsp;... He did the same thing&nbsp;... Hold on to my coin, Lucia. (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> After Dante leaves, Arius returns to the human world and Lucia defeats him.<ref>''Arius:'' You are not human! You are just a monster&nbsp;... a monster that I created! ''Lucia:'' Dante told me&nbsp;... Devils never cry! (''Devil May Cry 2'') Capcom, 2003</ref> \n\nIn ''Devil May Cry 5'', set several years after ''Devil May Cry 4'', Nero runs a mobile branch of Dante's Devil May Cry business.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sato |title=Devil May Cry 5 Shares A Closer Look At Nero And His Stylish Action |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/06/10/devil-may-cry-5-shares-closer-look-nero-stylish-action/ |website=Siliconera |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=June 10, 2018 }}</ref> He befriends Nico, a weapons artist and descendant of the gunsmith who crafted Dante's Ebony and Ivory handguns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mamiit |first1=Aaron |title=Here's Everything We Know On 'Devil May Cry 5': Release Date, Story, Gameplay, And More |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/230079/20180613/heres-everything-we-know-on-devil-may-cry-5-release-date-story-gameplay-and-more.htm |website=Tech Times |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=June 13, 2018 }}</ref> Nero's Devil Bringer arm from ''Devil May Cry 4'' is stolen; armed with a [[Prosthesis|prosthetic]] Devil Breaker created by Nico, he leaves with Dante and the demon hunter V to face their \"strongest foe yet\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arif |first1=Shabana |title=Devil May Cry 5 Director Talks Story Details, Playable Demo at Gamescom |url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2018/06/25/devil-may-cry-5-director-talks-story-details-playable-demo-at-gamescom |website=IGN |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Yin-Poole |first1=Wesley |title=Devil May Cry 5's third playable character is V |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-20-devil-may-cry-5s-third-playable-character-is-v |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=22 September 2018|date=September 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the series' timeline had placed ''Devil May Cry 4'' before ''Devil May Cry 2'', it was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] with the release of ''Devil May Cry 5''.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1093463399562993664|user=gypsyOtoko|title=We've changed it- now DMC 4 comes after 2! ^^;|author=Matt Walker|date=7 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Devil May Cry 5's Producer Explains the Series' Timeline Changes |url=https://www.ign.com/videos/2019/03/11/devil-may-cry-5s-producer-explains-the-series-timeline-changes |website=IGN |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'', developed by [[Ninja Theory]], is not part of the timeline and takes place in an alternate universe from the main series.<ref>{{cite web |title=DmC Devil May Cry Takes Place In A Parallel World With A Different Dante |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2011/10/31/dmc-devil-may-cry-takes-place-in-a-parallel-world-with-a-different-dante/|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n{{see also|Resident Evil 4#Development|l1=Development of Resident Evil 4}}\n[[File:Dante03.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|alt=16th-century painting of Dante Alighieri|The series is loosely based on the ''Divine Comedy'' by Dante Alighieri ''(pictured)''.]]\nAfter the completion of ''[[Resident Evil 2]]'' in 1998, preliminary work on a [[PlayStation 2]] installment of the ''Resident Evil'' series began by Team Little Devil under the direction of [[Hideki Kamiya]].<ref name=\"OkamiTree\">{{cite web|last=Mielke |first=Tuhin |publisher=1UP.com |date=August 18, 2006 |title=The Okami Family Tree |url=http://www.1up.com/features/retroactive-hideki-kamiya |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120605051116/http://www.1up.com/features/retroactive-hideki-kamiya |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=March 29, 2007 }}</ref> Early [[research and development]] included a trip to Spain to examine castles as a basis for the game's environments. Its prototype, however, was a radical departure from the ''Resident Evil'' formula and the [[survival horror]] genre. Kamiya rewrote the story and changed its premise, drawing from [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''<ref name=\"dmc3interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/postmortem-dmc3se|title=Postmortem on DMC3:SE|publisher=1UP.com|accessdate=23 June 2013|author=Mielke, James}}</ref><ref name=\"dmcscenario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil/column/vol010.html |title=\u30b7\u30ca\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u8a71 |author=Hideki Kamiya |date=July 2001 |work=Devil May Cry Column |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306002121/http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil/column/vol010.html |archivedate=6 March 2010 |df=dmy |author-link=Hideki Kamiya }}</ref> for ''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/094/094860p1.html| title= E3 2001: Interview with Shinji Mikami| publisher=IGN| date=May 17, 2001| accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of the original game, its sequel was not created by Kamiya or Team Little Devils.<ref>{{cite video game |title=[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]] |developer=Team Little Devils |publisher=[[Capcom#Branches and subsidiaries|Capcom Entertainment, Inc.]] |date=17 October 2001 |scene=staff credits}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/i_dmc2_ps2 |title=The Devil's in the detail |date=20 February 2003 |author=Kristan Reed |work=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Eurogamer Network Ltd. |accessdate=19 October 2010}}</ref> Although an unidentified director was placed in charge of the project, Capcom was dissatisfied with their work and assigned [[Hideaki Itsuno]] \"with only 4 to 5 months remaining in development\" to steer the project back on course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-devils-own-capcoms-hideaki-itsuno-on-a-decade-plus-with-dante|title=The Devil's Own: Capcom's Hideaki Itsuno on a Decade-Plus with Dante|date=29 June 2015|author=Bob Mackey |work=[[USgamer]] | accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> Despite Itsuno's limited time on the project, he is the only person credited as director in the final version of the game.<ref>{{cite video game |title=Devil May Cry 2 |developer=[[Capcom]] |publisher=[[Capcom#Branches and subsidiaries|Capcom Entertainment, Inc.]] |date=25 January 2003 |scene=staff credits}}</ref> According to [[Video game producer|producer]] Tsuyoshi Tanaka, the design aim was to make ''Devil May Cry 2'' bigger than its predecessor; Tanaka estimated that the game's environments were about nine times larger than the first.<ref>{{cite web| last = Steinberg| first = Scott|title = GameSpot Preview, page 1|date = 2002-09-18 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/devilmaycry2/news.html?sid=2880617|accessdate = 2008-07-20}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Devil May Cry 2''{{'s}} mixed reception, Capcom decided to develop the next game like the more critically-successful ''Devil May Cry''. Gameplay elements, such as environment size and battle engine, were reconsidered.<ref name=\"Gamedailybiz\">{{cite web|url=http://biz.gamedaily.com/industry/toppers/?id=9336 |title=Devil May Cry 3 Poised for Success |date=2005-04-06 |publisher=GameDaily |author=Brightman, James |accessdate=2007-04-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092141/http://biz.gamedaily.com/industry/toppers/?id=9336 |archivedate=September 29, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> In the original game, Vergil was killed by demons early and his soul was controlled by Mundus; [[Bingo Morihashi]] wanted to create an alternate universe in which Vergil was alive. However, Kamiya gave Morihashi the freedom to rework Vergil's backstory and make him a living teenager for ''Devil May Cry 3''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=211}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of ''Devil May Cry 4'' began shortly after its predecessor's success.<ref name=\"writing\">{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=208}}</ref> The development team had 80 members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.videogamesdaily.com/features/dmc4_iv_p3.asp|title=Devil May Cry 4: Kobayashi Interview|date=January 2, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2018|publisher=Video Games Daily}}</ref> A new protagonist was discussed many times at Capcom, but was not approved until producer [[Hiroyuki Kobayashi (producer)|Hiroyuki Kobayashi]] said that Dante had to be in the game.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=213}}</ref> Kobashi said before the game's release that they wanted to make Dante seem significantly more powerful than Nero, to create an obvious difference between the strength of a \"veteran\" compared to a \"rookie\".<ref name=\"very long interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3165697 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130116034927/http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3165697 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 16, 2013 |title=Previews: Devil May Cry 4 |author=James Mielke |website=1UP.com |date=January 31, 2008 |accessdate=February 25, 2008 }}</ref> Writer Morihashi collaborated with film director Yuji Shimomura, who worked on the earlier games. Morihashi left Capcom at one point, but returned at Itsuno's request. It took him a year to finish writing the game; he had difficulty with the characterization of Nero, the new protagonist. Dante returned as a supporting character.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry: 3142 Graphic Arts|publisher=Capcom, Udon Entertainment|year=2015|isbn=978-1927925485|pages=209}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the fourth game was a commercial and critical success, the staff considered rebooting the series because other game series had better sales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-09-22-dmc-devil-may-cry-interview |title=DmC: Devil May Cry|publisher=Eurogamer |date=September 22, 2010 |accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref> They chose Ninja Theory, impressed with their work on ''[[Heavenly Sword]]'' (which the staff thought would work with a ''Devil May Cry'' game).<ref name=\"xbuttoninter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2012-10-17|title=The X Button In the Details|publisher=Anime News Network |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=October 17, 2012|author=Ciolek, Todd}}</ref> However, in 2013 Itsuno expressed interest in developing a fifth installment.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dualshockers.com/2013/10/21/dragons-dogma-director-wants-to-make-a-sequel-on-ps4-also-rival-schools-3-and-devil-may-cry-5/ |title = Dragon's Dogma Director Wants to Make a Sequel on PS4, Also Rival Schools 3 and Devil May Cry 5|date = October 21, 2013}}</ref> It was originally thought that Itsuno intended for the series to go on hiatus or end if ''Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition'' was not a commercial success,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/game/content/?p=19420&redirect_stop=1 |title=\u7b2c\u4e09\u5341\u4e09\u56de\u3000\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u304c\u6b69\u3080\u9b54\u754c\u3078\u306e\u9053\uff08\u5f8c\u7de8\uff09 |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=2015-06-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612163031/http://www.capcom.co.jp/game/content/?p=19420&redirect_stop=1 |archivedate=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but he said in a GameSpot interview that the series' future did not depend on ''Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sales. He alleviated fears that ''DmC: Devil May Cry''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sales would kill the series, confirming that Capcom was satisfied with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/devil-may-crys-future-isnt-tied-to-how-well-devil-/1100-6428432/|title=Devil May Cry's Future isn't Tied to how well Devil May Cry 4: Special Edition sells}}</ref> In mid-January 2016, Itsuno tweeted that he had begun work on a new project.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=tomqe|author=Hideaki Itsuno|number=687098966815543297|date=13 January 2016|title=Happy New Year! The next project has already begun. Please wait to look forward to but can not be announced.}}</ref> Reuben Langdon and Johnny Yong Bosch, who had done voice acting and motion capture for Dante and Nero in ''Devil May Cry 4'', took pictures of themselves in motion-capture gear in March 2016; this led to speculation that a new ''Devil May Cry'' game was in development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gametyrant.com/news/screen-shot-of-mocap-actors-lead-to-devil-may-cry-5-rumor|title=Screen Shot Of Mocap Actors Lead To DEVIL MAY CRY 5 Rumor|website=GameTyrant|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref> According to Capcom Vancouver, \"It's not a game that [they] announced that [they are] working on at [their] studio\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2016/08/01/devil-may-cry-5-capcom-weighs-in/ |title = Capcom Posts Vague Answer when Quizzed About Devil May Cry 5|date = August 2, 2016}}</ref> On May 17, 2018, the domain name \"DevilMayCry5.com\" was registered under Capcom's Onamae domain register.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gematsu.com/2018/06/devil-may-cry-5-domain-name-registered | title=Devil May Cry 5 domain name registered| date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry 5'', featuring the return of Dante and Nero, was confirmed at [[E3 2018]] for release the following year.<ref>[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-devil-may-cry-5-confirmed-at-xbox-one-pres/1100-6459608/ E3 2018: Devil May Cry 5 Confirmed At Xbox One Press Conference], GameSpot</ref>  Most of the team had worked on the recently-released ''Resident Evil 7'', and were experienced with the [[game engine]]; Itsuno was influenced by his work in ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]'' to provide content appealing to new gamers, but also felt that making the game challenging would appeal to long-time fans.<ref name=\"itsuno\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/29/18284532/devil-may-cry-5-hideaki-itsuno-interview-gdc-2019|title=Devil May Cry 5's director wanted to prove pure action games still had a place|date=March 29, 2019|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=June 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629173831/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/29/18284532/devil-may-cry-5-hideaki-itsuno-interview-gdc-2019|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Other members of the staff had worked on the reboot game ''[[DmC: Devil May Cry]]'', but the Osaka team was more willing to make a sequel to the fourth installment of the main series. The team listened to fan opinion about previous games, to ensure that the new game appealed to them; an \"auto\" mode facilitated combos.<ref name=\"osaka\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/27/devil-may-cry-5-interview-capcom-satisfying-fans-balancing-difficulty-learning-ninja-theory/|publisher=VG247|accessdate=June 29, 2019|title=Devil May Cry 5 interview: Capcom on satisfying fans, balancing difficulty and learning from Ninja Theory|date=September 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629173827/https://www.vg247.com/2018/09/27/devil-may-cry-5-interview-capcom-satisfying-fans-balancing-difficulty-learning-ninja-theory/|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Itsuno was moved to tears by a film in which three robots combined into a giant robot to overcome their foe, and wanted to create similar moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/devil-may-cry-5s-director-tells-us-how-they-made-combat-1833642299|title=Devil May Cry 5's Director Tells Us How They Made Combat Feel So Damn Good|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=June 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080028/https://kotaku.com/devil-may-cry-5s-director-tells-us-how-they-made-combat-1833642299|archive-date=9 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He wanted to convey the style of a Hollywood movie such as [[Marvel Studios|Marvel]]'s ''[[Avengers (film series)|Avengers]]'' series.<ref name=\"ruliweb\">{{cite web|url=https://m.ruliweb.com/news/read/117389#csidx3745535f1bbf4c0b1cb92aa605dd106|title=\ub370\ube4c \uba54\uc774 \ud06c\ub77c\uc774 5, \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\ubb3c \uac19\uc740 \uc52c \uc794\ub729 \ub123\uc5c8\ub2e4|publisher=Ruliweb|accessdate=June 30, 2019}}</ref> Kamiya, currently working at [[PlatinumGames]], was interested in making a remake of the first installment and a crossover game with Dante and [[Bayonetta (character)|Bayonetta]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.siliconera.com/2017/11/20/hideki-kamiya-wants-viewtiful-joe-dmc-remake-dante-x-bayonneta-crossover/ | title = Hideki Kamiya Wants To Do A Viewtiful Joe Or DMC Remake, And A Dante x Bayonetta Crossover | date = 20 November 2017 | work = Siliconera }}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n===Light novels===\nThe series has a number of print adaptations. Two [[Devil May Cry (novels)|''Devil May Cry'' light novels]], written by Shinya Goikeda and illustrated by [[Shirow Miwa]], were published in Japan in 2002 and translated and published in the United States in 2006. The first, ''Devil May Cry Volume 1'', was published in Japan in conjunction with the release of the first game and explores Dante in an adventure set before the events of the game. The second, entitled ''Devil May Cry Volume 2'' in the US, was published in Japan to coincide with the release of the second game and is set after the events of the first game. [[Tokyopop]] published the books in the United States in June and November 2006, respectively.<ref name=\"AmazonDMC1\">{{cite book| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry Volume 1| isbn = 1598164503| author1 = Capcom| last2 = Goikeda| first2 = Shinya| date = June 13, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"AmazonDMC2\">{{cite book| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry Volume 2| isbn = 1598164511}}</ref>\n\nBingo Morihashi wrote a ''Devil May Cry 4'' novel entitled ''Devil May Cry 4 Deadly Fortune''. The two-volume novel, published in Japan in 2009, has a number of scenes which were not included in the original game due to time constraints.<ref name=\"novel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/04/_deadly_fortune.html|title=\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u30e1\u30a4\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\uff14 -Deadly Fortune-1|publisher=[[Capcom]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=2 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603031554/http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/04/_deadly_fortune.html|archive-date=3 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/07/_deadly_fortune_1.html |title=\u30c7\u30d3\u30eb\u30e1\u30a4\u30af\u30e9\u30a4\uff14 -Deadly Fortune-2 |publisher=[[Capcom]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=2 May 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602104915/http://www.capcom-fc.com/devil4column/2009/07/_deadly_fortune_1.html |archivedate= 2 June 2013 |df= }}</ref> A prequel novel by Morihashi, set before ''Devil May Cry 5'' and leading to the beginning of the game, was published on March 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite book|title=Devil May Cry 5 -Before the Nightmare-|publisher=Kadokawa|year=2019|isbn=978-4041080924}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and manga===\nThree issues of a comic adaptation of the first game were published by the Canadian [[Dreamwave Productions]] in 2004, but the series was left unfinished when the company went bankrupt the following year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=4625 | title=Dreamwave Productions closes up shop |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] | accessdate=April 23, 2007}}</ref> On July 25, 2008, [[WildStorm]] (a [[DC Comics]] [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]]) and [[Capcom]] announced that they would collaborate on a ''Devil May Cry'' [[American comic book|comic-book]] series. Details about the series were planned to be announced at a later date,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5030369/resident-evil-and-devil-may-cry-comics-on-the-way |title=Resident Evil And Devil May Cry Comics On The Way |author=Mike Fahey |publisher=Kotaku |date=July 29, 2008 |accessdate=August 31, 2008}}</ref> but no new information has been provided.\n\nTwo volumes of a planned three-part [[Devil May Cry 3 (manga)|''Devil May Cry 3'' manga]] series have been published in Japan and the United States. Set a year before the events of ''Devil May Cry 3'', the manga describes how the characters come to be where they are at the beginning of the game.\n\nOn March 7, 2019, Capcom announced that a tie-in manga entitled ''Devil May Cry 5 Visions of V'' would be serialized on the Japanese manga-hosting site Line Manga (LINE \u30de\u30f3\u30ac).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/devil5/news/book190308.html |title=Visions of V Announced|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> The manga's prologue was published before the serialization began. Illustrated by Tomio Ogata, the manga (only available in Japan) would update every other Sunday beginning on April 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ExtraVirgin_OO/status/1103624818874703872 |title=Tomio Ogata's Visions of V|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://manga.line.me/product/periodic?id=Z0000410 |title=Visions of V LINE MANGA|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-03-09/devil-may-cry-5-game-gets-manga-spinoff-about-v/.144360|title=Devil May Cry 5 Game Gets Manga Spinoff About V|date=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nAn [[anime]] series, ''[[Devil May Cry: The Animated Series]]'', premiered on Japan's [[Wowow]] TV network on June 12, 2007. The 12-episode series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://activeanime.com/html/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=3851 |title=ActiveAnime:Devil May Cry Anime and Pre Site Opening |accessdate=January 23, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070417100910/http://activeanime.com/html/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=3851 |archivedate=April 17, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dmc-tv.com | title=Devil May Cry anime official site (in Japanese) | accessdate=January 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Devil May Cry: The Animated Series|date=2019-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Devil_May_Cry:_The_Animated_Series&oldid=892409674|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> produced by [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]], was directed by Shin Itagaki. Bingo Morihashi, a writer of the third and fourth games, was one of its writers.\n\nIn November 2018, [[Adi Shankar]] announced that he had acquired the rights to produce a ''Devil May Cry'' animated series. Shankar, who has been completing a similar [[Castlevania (TV series)|animated series]] for Konami's ''[[Castlevania]]'' franchise, said that he considered both series part of a shared \"bootleg multiverse\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/16/devil-may-cry-series-joins-castlevania-in-new-multiverse-from-adi-shankar | title = Devil May Cry Series Joins Castlevania In New Multiverse From Adi Shankar | first = David | last = Griffin | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nOn February 28, 2011, it was announced that [[Screen Gems]] (which made ''Resident Evil'' into a [[Resident Evil (film series)|film series]]) had purchased feature-film rights to the ''Devil May Cry'' series.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118033032?refCatId=13 | work=Variety | first1=Andrew | last1=Stewart | first2=Marc | last2=Graser | title='Devil May Cry' videogame heading to bigscreen | date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> Kyle Ward would write the screenplay for the film (based on ''DmC: Devil May Cry''), which would be Dante's origin story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/e3-2011-devil-may-cry-film-based-on-new-game-6318318|title=E3 2011: Devil May Cry Film Based On New Game|author=Tom Magrino|publisher=Gamespot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crossmap.com/news/devil-may-cry-movie-release-date-updates-storyline-what-this-game-turned-movie-is-going-to-turn-out-to-be-15585|title=Devil May Cry Movie Release Date, Updates, Storyline: What this Game Turned Movie is Going to Turn Out to Be|publisher=Cross Map|last=Lavigne|first=Patty|date=January 15, 2015|access-date=December 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208174111/http://www.crossmap.com/news/devil-may-cry-movie-release-date-updates-storyline-what-this-game-turned-movie-is-going-to-turn-out-to-be-15585|archive-date=December 8, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthhealthmag.com/articles/32990/20160118/devil-may-cry-movie-movie-adaptation.htm|title='Devil May Cry' Movie Adaptation Still Happening? Norman Reedus Or Brad Pitt To Play Dante?|publisher=Youth Health Mag|last=Rajasekhar|first=Gouravaram|date=January 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Plays===\nCapcom produced ''Sengoku Basara vs. Devil May Cry'' a staged amalgam of the ''Devil May Cry'' and ''[[Sengoku Basara]]'' series, in August 2015. In the play, Dante, Lady, Trish, and Vergil encounter mysterious historical ruins while chasing a devil and are sent back in time to Japan's [[Warring States period]]; there, they meet Date Masamune, Sanada Yukimura and other characters from the ''Sengoku Basara'' franchise. The play ran at the AiiA 2.5 Theater in Tokyo for 18 performances. [[Masanari Ujigawa]] wrote and directed the play, and [[Hideaki Itsuno]] and [[Izaki Matsuno]] collaborated on the scenery. [[Kazushi Miyakoda]] and [[Tetsuya Yamaura]] were the producers, supervised by [[Hiroyuki Kobayashi (producer)|Hiroyuki Kobayashi]] and [[Makoto Yamamoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-08/more-cast-revealed-for-sengoku-basara-vs-devil-may-cry-stage-play/.87955|title=More Cast Revealed for Sengoku Basara vs. Devil May Cry Stage Play|date=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry: The Live Hacker'', a musical, ran for 13 performances in March 2019 at [[Zepp|Zepp DiverCity]] in Tokyo. Jun Yoriko wrote and directed the musical and its video,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-01-18/devil-may-cry-the-live-hacker-reveals-cast-members-in-costume/.142266|title=Devil May Cry: The Live Hacker Reveals Cast Members in Costume|date=January 18, 2019}}</ref> and a DVD was released in late August of that year.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dmc-livehacker.com/ | title=Devil May Cry \u30fcthe Live Hacker\u30fc}}</ref>\n\n==In other games==\n''Devil May Cry'' characters appear in the [[PlayStation]] versions of the ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'' games, another Capcom series created by Hideki Kamiya; Dante is a playable character in the [[PlayStation 2]] port of the first ''Viewtiful Joe''. The [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]] version of ''[[Viewtiful Joe: Red Hot Rumble]]'' also includes Dante and costumes based on Vergil, Trish, Sparda, Marionette, and Plasma.\n\nIn a deal between Capcom and [[Atlus]], ''[[Megami Tensei]]'' character designer [[Kazuma Kaneko]] created Dante and Vergil's demonic forms in ''Devil May Cry 3''. In return, Atlus included Dante in his ''Devil May Cry 2'' costume as a character in an enhanced release of ''[[Shin Megami Tensei: Nocturne]]'' (''Maniax'' in Japan). The English localization of ''Nocturne'' was based on the game's ''Maniax'' edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlus.com/smt/faqs.html|title=Atlus USA presents Shin Megami Tensei: Nocturne|publisher=[[Atlus]]|accessdate=April 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDante and Trish are playable characters in ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 3: Fate of Two Worlds]]'', and Vergil, Dante and Trish are playable characters in its ''[[Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3]]'' update. Dante and Vergil retain their Kazuma Kaneko-designed Devil Trigger forms, since they are based on the third game of the ''Devil May Cry'' series.\n\nThe ''DmC: Devil May Cry'' version of Dante is a playable character in ''[[PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale]]'', and he is a playable character in ''[[Project X Zone]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS as half of a pair with ''[[Darkstalkers]]''{{'}} [[Demitri Maximoff]]; Lady is a separate character. Dante returns in its sequel, ''[[Project X Zone 2]]'', with Vergil; Vergil's future self, Nelo Angelo, is a rival character.\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG Series Reviews\n| updated = March 11, 2019\n| game1 = [[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]\n| mc1 = (PS2) 94 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry |title=''Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game2 = [[Devil May Cry 2]] \n| mc2 = (PS2) 68 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-2 |title=''Devil May Cry 2'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game3 = [[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening]]\n| mc3 = (PS2) 87 <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3-special-edition |title=''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 66 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-3-special-edition |title=''Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game4 = [[Devil May Cry 4]]\n| mc4 = (PS3) 84 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/devil-may-cry-4 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(X360) 84 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/devil-may-cry-4 |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 78<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-4 |title=''Devil May Cry 4'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game5 = [[DmC: Devil May Cry]]\n| mc5 = (X360) 86 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PS3) 85 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><br>(PC) 85 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/dmc |title=''DmC Devil May Cry'' Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| game6 = [[Devil May Cry 5]]\n| mc6 = (PC) 90 <ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for PC Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><br>(PS4) 88 <ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for PlayStation 4 Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><br>(XONE) 87 <ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/devil-may-cry-5|title=Devil May Cry 5 for Xbox One Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nBy December 31, 2019, the ''Devil May Cry'' series had sold 21 million units worldwide;<ref>[http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/salesdata.html CAPCOM | Game Series Sales]</ref> each installment was a Capcom Platinum Title, selling over a million units.<ref name=\"capcomplatinum\">{{cite web|url=http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/data/million.html |title=Platinum Titles |publisher=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=April 4, 2007 |date=January 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211163520/http://ir.capcom.co.jp/english/data/million.html |archivedate=February 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> As of December 2019, ''Devil May Cry 5'' had sold 3.1&nbsp;million copies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Platinum Titles |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/million.html |website=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201214236/http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/million.html |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe series has received generally-positive reviews. In 2010, [[IGN]] ranked ''Devil May Cry'' number 42 and ''Devil May Cry 3'' number 18 on its \"Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/42 |title=Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |publisher=IGN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201231437/http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/42 |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/18 |title=Top 100 PlayStation 2 Games |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |publisher=IGN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103190544/http://ie.ign.com/top/ps2-games/18 |archivedate=January 3, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' gameplay has been praised as innovative.<ref name=\"Eurogamer\">{{cite web|author=John Bye |date=2001-08-12 |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2281 |title=Devil May Cry Review |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=2008-07-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930035826/http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2281 |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gamecritics\"/><ref name=\"ElectricPlayground\">{{cite web|author=James Tapia| url=http://www.elecplay.com/reviews_article.php?article=7180| title=Devil May Cry Review| publisher=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]| accessdate=2008-07-20| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610080414/http://www.elecplay.com/reviews_article.php?article=7180 <!--Added by H3llBot-->| archivedate=2008-06-10}}</ref> ''Devil May Cry'' has been cited as beginning a subgenre of \"extreme combat\" action games, which focus on powerful heroes fighting hordes of foes with stylized action.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bateman | first = Chris | author2 = Richard Boon | title = 21st Century Game Design | publisher = Charles River Media | pages = [https://archive.org/details/21stcenturygamed0000bate/page/246 246\u2013247] | date = August 29, 2005 | isbn = 978-1-58450-429-0 | title-link = 21st Century Game Design }}</ref> It has been described as the first game that \"successfully captured the twitch-based, relentlessly free-flowing gameplay style of so many classic [[2D computer graphics|2D]] action games\".<ref name=\"Review1\">{{cite web|last= Ahmed|first= Shahed |date= October 17, 2001|title = Gamespot Devil May Cry review| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/devilmaycry/review.html|accessdate = March 29, 2007 | publisher=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> The series is the standard against which other [[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[hack and slash]] action games are measured, with comparisons in reviews of games such as ''[[God of War (2005 video game)|God of War]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= God of War|publisher=IGN|url= http://ps2.ign.com/objects/661/661321.html#previews| accessdate= April 3, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| date= June 16, 2005| publisher=Playstation World| title= God of War Review |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=120641&site=psw&skip=yes| accessdate= April 3, 2003}}</ref> ''[[Chaos Legion]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last= Varanini|first= Giancarlo| publisher=[[GameSpot]]| date= August 4, 2003| title= Chaos Legion review| url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/chaoslegion/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;review| accessdate= April 3, 2007}}</ref> and ''[[Blood Will Tell]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bedigian |first=Louis |publisher=Gamezone |date=September 29, 2004 |title=Blood Will Tell review |url=http://ps2.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r22035.htm |accessdate= April 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070412062309/http://ps2.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r22035.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Devil May Cry 5'' has three protagonists with distinctive abilities, increasing the number of moves available.<ref name=\"vgamer\">{{cite web |title=Devil May Cry 5 review |url=https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review |website=VideoGamer.com |date=6 March 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307112327/https://www.videogamer.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review |archive-date=7 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"IGN Review\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2019/03/06/devil-may-cry-5-review|title=Devil May Cry 5 Review|last=Saltzman|first=Mitchell|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dailytelegraph\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Olivia |title=Devil May Cry 5 review: Dante and friends return in a stylish and supremely fun demon-hunting blockbuster |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/devil-may-cry-5-review-dante-friends-return-stylish-supremely/ |accessdate=6 March 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306163646/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/devil-may-cry-5-review-dante-friends-return-stylish-supremely/ |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Hiroyuki Kobayashi, the team's work on ''Devil May Cry 4'' influenced Capcom's ''[[Dragon's Dogma]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/dragons-dogma-interview-part-1-from-devils-to-dragons/|title=Dragon's Dogma Interview Part 1: From Devils To Dragons|website=Siliconera|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponse to the series' narrative has been mixed, despite Dante's increased popularity.<ref name=\"Gamecrush\">{{cite web |author=Rocco Inzauto, Edward |url=http://gamecrush.blogspot.com/2007/02/top-10-most-badass-video-game-charaters.html |title=Top 10: Most Badass Video Game Characters |date=February 25, 2007 |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129042015/http://gamecrush.blogspot.com/2007/02/top-10-most-badass-video-game-charaters.html |archivedate=January 29, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Screwattack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelastboss.com/post.phtml?pk=2160 |title=Top ten coolest games |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809013318/http://www.thelastboss.com/post.phtml?pk=2160 |archivedate=August 9, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series' popularity led to a line of ''Devil May Cry'' action figures produced by Toycom,<ref name=\"Actionfigures\">{{cite web|author=Borst, Brian |url=http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=2243 |title=Devil May Cry Action Figures review |date=June 1, 2003 |accessdate=April 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516220713/http://www.popcultureshock.com/reviews.php?id=2243 |archivedate=May 16, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}<br />{{cite web|author=Borst, Brian |url=http://www.popcultureshock.com/pcs-reviews.php?id=2243 |title=Devil May Cry Action Figures |work=Pop Culture Shock |date=June 4, 2003 |accessdate=January 16, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116193119/http://www.popcultureshock.com/pcs-reviews.php?id=2243 |archivedate=January 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> and [[Kaiyodo]] produced a ''Devil May Cry 2'' and ''Devil May Cry 3'' Dante action figure.<ref name=\"AmazonDMC2 figs\">{{cite web|title=Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry 2 Action Figures |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000HX7YTK |accessdate=April 23, 2007 |df=mdy }}{{dead link|date=February 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"AmazonDMC3\">{{cite web| title = Amazon.com Listing for Devil May Cry 3 Dante Revoltech action figure| url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000GBN2Y4| accessdate = April 23, 2007}}</ref> \n\nAccording to a gamecritics.com reviewer, the story was overly short and the characters underdeveloped.<ref name=\"Gamecritics\">{{cite web|author=Mike Doolittle |date=2001-11-28 |title=Devil May Cry review |url=http://www.gamecritics.com/review/devilmaycry/main.php |accessdate=2008-07-20 |publisher=Gamecritics.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922214620/http://www.gamecritics.com/review/devilmaycry/main.php |archivedate=2008-09-22 }}</ref> Dante's cockiness was noted as largely absent from ''Devil May Cry 2''.<ref name=\"Gamespy\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.gamespy.com/reviews/february03/dmc2ps2/ |title=Devil May Cry 2 review |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=15 April 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724215125/http://archive.gamespy.com/reviews/february03/dmc2ps2/ |archivedate=24 July 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Railey, Dave\">{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/game/playstation-3-xbox-360/devil-may-cry/hd-collection |title=Devil May Cry: HD Collection |work=[[Anime News Network]] |author=Railey, Dave |date=16 April 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615232002/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/game/playstation-3-xbox-360/devil-may-cry/hd-collection |archivedate=15 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n''Devil May Cry 3'' and its relationships among the cast in the narrative were found to be superior to Kamiya's original version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/devil-may-cry-3-10/2/|title=Devil May Cry 3|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|publisher=[[Future plc|Future]]|date=July 28, 2004|accessdate=July 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725003106/https://www.gamesradar.com/devil-may-cry-3-10/2/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/04/devil-may-cry-a-series-retrospective-part-iii/|title=Devil May Cry: a series retrospective - part III|work=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Verizon Communications]]|author=Doee, Mark|date=February 4, 2008|accessdate=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725214710/https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/04/devil-may-cry-a-series-retrospective-part-iii/|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3/592530p2.html|title=Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening|work=[[GameSpy]]|publisher=IGN|author=Lopez, Miguel|date=March 1, 2005|accessdate=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026061519/http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/devil-may-cry-3/592530p2.html|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dante's dynamic with Nero in the following game was praised, with critics saying that neither overshadowed the other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-4-review/1900-6185608/|title=Devil May Cry 4 Review|website=GameSpot|accessdate=June 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627005357/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-4-review/1900-6185608/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GIDMC4review\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Game Informer]]| author= Joe, Juba | url=http://gameinformer.com/Games/Review/200803/R08.0205.1105.44993.htm | title= Game Informer: Devil May Cry 4 Review| accessdate=5 February 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080512084303/http://gameinformer.com/Games/Review/200803/R08.0205.1105.44993.htm |archivedate = 12 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"IGNDMC4review\">{{cite web| website= IGN| author= Haynes, Jeff| url= http://ps3.ign.com/articles/849/849224p1.html| title= IGN: Devil May Cry 4 Review (PS3)| accessdate=5 February 2008| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120101200755/http://ps3.ign.com/articles/849/849224p1.html| archive-date= 1 January 2012| url-status= live}}</ref> According to GameCored, many fans were eager to play as Vergil again in ''Devil May Cry 5'' and were disappointed that he was not a playable character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecored.com/devil-may-cry-5-jugar-como-vergil/|title=Devil May Cry 5: \u00bfPodr\u00e1s jugar como Vergil?|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=GameCord|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> ''HobbyConsolas'' hacked into the game to find code which mentioned the character's name, but was unable to determine if Vergil would be playable as downloadable content.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/noticias/devil-may-cry-5-descubren-codigo-cuarto-personaje-jugable-video-386436|title=Devil May Cry 5 - Descubren en el c\u00f3digo a un cuarto personaje jugable (v\u00eddeo)|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=HobbyConsolas|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> ''Devil May Cry 5''{{'}}s handling of its characters and their connections was well-received.<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/devil-may-cry-5-review-comeback-album/1900-6417099 |title=Devil May Cry 5 Review|last=Espineli|first=Matt|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vgamer\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{ref